{"title_page": "8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n| image=8th Canadian Hussars Princess Louises badge.jpg\n| image_size = 150\n|caption= Regimental [[cap badge]]\n|dates= 1869\u2013present\n|country= Canada\n|branch= [[Canadian Army]]\n|type= Armoured Reconnaissance\n|role= Reconnaissance\n|size=\n|command_structure=[[37 Canadian Brigade Group]]\n|garrison=[[Moncton]]\n|garrison_label=\n|ceremonial_chief=[[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n|ceremonial_chief_label=Colonel-in-chief\n|nickname=The Crazy Eights\n|patron=[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll]]\n|motto={{lang-la|Regi patriaeque fidelis|lit=Faithful to king and country}}\n|colors=\n|colors_label=\n|march=\"The 8th Hussars\"\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|identification_symbol = VIII CH\n|identification_symbol_label = Abbreviation\n}}\nThe '''8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)''' (VIII CH) is the longest-serving armoured [[regiment]] in the [[Canadian Army]]. It was formed on the 4 April 1848 in New Brunswick where it has served continually ever since. Today it is a reserve armoured reconnaissance regiment with two squadrons. Its Regimental Headquarters (RHQ) and A Squadron are located in [[Moncton]] with B Squadron located in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]].\n\nIn 1957 its name was chosen for the formation of a new Regular Force regiment to serve in addition to the reserve regiment. The Regular regiment served in [[CFB Gagetown|Gagetown, New Brunswick]], [[CFB Petawawa|Petawawa, Ontario]], the Sinai, Cyprus, Iserlohn (Fort Beausejour), Soest, and Lahr, West Germany. The Regular Force regiment was disbanded in 1998.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest beginnings of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) have traditionally been traced to the year 1775 in the Colony of Virginia where Captain John Saunders, of Princess Anne County, raised a troop of cavalry at his own expense to fight for the Crown against the Colonial rebels. This unusual Regiment included riflemen, grenadiers, artillery and cavalry, and it never knew defeat during the American conflict for independence. In September 1783, the Regiment as an entity sailed for Nova Scotia and reached Saint John on 27 September 1783. A large number of these Loyalists soldiers settled in the Saint John and Kennebecasis valleys by Loyalist soldiers, had a military tradition and indeed an effective militia. In 1839, the York County Troop, known for a time as the York Light Dragoons, was mobilized for service in the Aroostook War, a conflict with American lumbermen that never quite came to open fighting. For four months they patrolled the border and roads between Woodstock, Fredericton and Saint John. By 1848, eleven troops of cavalry were in existence. These troops included Hampton Troop of Cavalry, Assekeag Troop of Cavalry, Apohaqui Troop of Cavalry, Upham Troop of Cavalry, Johnston Troop of Cavalry, Shediac Troop of Cavalry, Springfield Troop of Cavalry, among others.\n\nBy authority of Militia General Order No 1 of 4 April 1848, these eleven independent troops were united to form a Regiment entitled the New Brunswick Yeomanry Cavalry. It is this date that is officially recognized as the formation date of the 8th Canadian Hussars.\n*Redesignated 31 May 1872 as the 8th Regiment of Cavalry\n*Redesignated 18 July 1884 as the 8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick Regiment of Cavalry\n*Redesignated 1 January 1893 8th \"Princess Louise's New Brunswick Hussars\"\n*Redesignated 11 February 1941 as the 2nd (Reserve) Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars\n*Redesignated 1 April 1941 as the 5th (Reserve) Armoured Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars\n*Redesignated 4 February 1949 as the 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars (5th Armoured Regiment)\n*Redesignated 29 January 1957 as the 2/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) upon the formation of the Canadian Army (Regular) 1/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n*1 January 1960 the 2/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were redesignated as 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) (Militia) and the 1/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were redesignated as the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n*15 April 1993 the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) (Militia) and the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were amalgamated and redesignated as the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)<ref name=Vol3>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\n===South African War===\n[[Image:8CH camp flag.jpg|thumb|The camp flag of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's).]]The regiment contributed volunteers for the Canadian Contingents that served in South Africa.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\nThe 6th Regiment, Canadian Mounted Rifles Battalion, CEF, was authorized on 7 November 1914 and embarked for England on 17 July 1915. It disembarked in France on 24 October 1915, where it continued to train until 2 January 1916 when its personnel were absorbed by the [[4th Battalion, Canadian Mounted Rifles]] and the [[5th Battalion, Canadian Mounted Rifles, CEF]]. The regiment disbanded on 18 February 1918.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Second World War===\nThe Second World War provided the regiment's first opportunity for active service as a formed unit. The regiment mobilized as the 4th Canadian Motorcycle Regiment, CASF (8 NBH) on 24 May 1940. It was converted to armour and redesignated as the \"8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars) CAC, CASF\", on 9 February 1941; as the 5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, CASF, on 11 February 1941.\nThe regiment embarked for Britain on 9 October 1941\n\nThe regiment landed in Italy on 19 December 1943 as a unit of the 5th Armoured Brigade, [[5th Canadian Armoured Division]]. It was renamed as the \"5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, CAC, CASF\", on 15 October 1943.\nThe regiment [[Allied invasion of Italy|landed in Italy]] on 19 December 1943 at Naples and saw action soon and frequently thereafter. The regiment fought in the Liri Valley, the Melfa Crossing, Ceprano, The Gothic Line, Missano Ridge, Coriano, the [[Lamone (river)|Lamone River]] Crossing, and Coventello where it distinguished itself.\n\nIt moved to North-West Europe on 17 February 1945 as part of [[Operation Goldflake]]. The Hussars sailed from Italy to Southern France, and then moved by rail to Northwest Europe. After refitting the tanks, the regiment went into action in the Netherlands, breaking through to Putten in mid-April. The regiment then moved north for the final actions of the war at the Delfzijl Pocket where 3,000 German soldiers surrendered to the regiment. It was renamed as the \"5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, RCAC, CASF\", on 2 August 1945.\n\nOn 26 January 1946, the regiment arrived in Halifax and the next day reached Sussex, New Brunswick where it was demobilized. The overseas regiment disbanded on 15 February 1946.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===Post World War II===\nIn 1950, the regiment was called upon to provide men for service with the Special Force which was raised and deployed to Korea, and in 1951 \"Y\" Troop was organized for service with the 27th Canadian Infantry Brigade in Germany.\n\nOn 29 January 1957, it was decided that a third armoured regiment would be formed in the [[Land Force Command|Canadian Army]]. As a result, the regiment was honoured with the privilege of providing its name to the new regiment. This resulted in the change of the regiment's name to the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's). The Regular Regiment served in [[CFB Gagetown|Gagetown]], New Brunswick, Petawawa, Ontario, the Sinai, Cyprus, Iserlohn (Fort Beausejour), Soest and Lahr, West Germany.\n\nCpl. Paul R. Wallace and Tpr. Adrian A. Bons died while deployed to the Sinai as part of the United Nations Emergency Force on 27 November 1964.\n\nIn the summer of 1965, the regiment was deployed from their base at [[Petawawa, Ontario]] on a peacekeeping mission for the United Nations to the island nation of Cyprus. Tpr. Lennard W. Nass died on 27 September 1966 while deployed to Cyprus as part of the United Nations Force in Cyprus.\n\nThe regiment has participated in several \"aid to the civil authority\" missions in recent history. In the summer of 1990 the regiment sent a troop sized force to the province of Quebec in Cougars to assist in Canadian Forces Operations in the [[Oka Crisis]]. In the [[1998 Ice Storm]], the regiment provided a platoon-sized force to assist in the maintenance of infrastructure in the community of [[St. George, New Brunswick]]. In the fall of 1998, the regiment provided soldiers to the recovery effort for Swiss Air Flight 111.\n\nIn 2004, 8CH became an armoured reconnaissance unit, in place of its previous designation as simply an armoured unit. Along with this trade change the unit was given the new [[Mercedes-Benz]] [[Mercedes-Benz G-Class|G-Wagon]], a Jeep-like vehicle more suited to their new role as reconnaissance. The unit is stationed at the Moncton and Sussex detachments of [[CFB Gagetown]], [[New Brunswick]]. Its [[Colonel-in-Chief]] is [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]].\n\n===War in Afghanistan===\nThe regiment contributed an aggregate of more than 20% of its authorized strength to the various Task Forces which served in Afghanistan between 2002 and 2014.<ref name=\"pm.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2014/05/09/south-west-asia-theatre-honours |title=South-West Asia Theatre Honours |accessdate=2014-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231549/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2014/05/09/south-west-asia-theatre-honours |archivedate=2014-05-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Lineage chart===\nLineage of the units of the 8th Canadian Hussars:<ref>{{cite web|title=8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)|url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par1/arm-bli/8CH-eng.asp|website=Volume 3, Part 1: Armour, Artillery and Field Engineer Regiments \u2013 Armour Regiments|publisher=Directorate of History and Heritage|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n{{chart top|width=100%|Lineage}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|aa812| | |12WCR| | | | |aa812=1812|12WCR=1st and 2nd Bn, Westmorland County Regt}}\n{{chart|aa815|F|~|Dbndd| | | | |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa815=1815}}\n{{chart|aa864|:| | | | | |Ippvy|Ippvy=Independent troops of cavy|aa864=1864}}\n{{chart|aa869|:| | | | | | NBYC|aa869=1869|NBYC=New Brunswick Regt of Yeomanry Cavy}}\n{{chart|aa872|:| | | | | |8Cavy|aa872=1872|8Cavy=8th Regt of Cavy}}\n{{chart|aa884|:| | | | | |8PLNB|8PLNB=8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick Regt of Cavy|aa884=1884}}\n{{chart|aa893|:| | | | | |8PLNB|8PLNB=8th <small>\"Princess Louise's New Brunswick Hussars\"</small>|aa893=1893}}\n{{chart|aa914|:| | 6CMR| | |!| |6CMR=6th Regt, Canadian Mounted Rifles, <small>CEF</small>|aa914=1914}}\n{{chart|aa916|:| |A45CM| | |!| |A45CM=''Absorbed by 4th and 5th Canadian Mounted Rifles Bn, <small>CEF</small>''|aa916=1916}}\n{{chart|aa918|:|F|Dbndd| | |!| |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa918=1918}}\n{{chart| nbsp|:|:| | | | | |!| |nbsp=&nbsp;}}\n{{chart|aa940|:|:| 4CMR| | |!| |aa940=1940|4CMR=4th Canadian Motorcycle Regt, <small>CASF (8 NBH)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa941|:|:| 8PLH| |28PLH|28PLH=2nd <small>(Reserve)</small> Regt, 8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars|8PLH=8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars, <small>CAC, CASF</small>|aa941=1941}}\n{{chart|aa941|:|:| 5AR | |5A8PL|5A8PL=5th <small>(Reserve)</small> Armd Regt, 8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars|5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), CASF</small>|aa941=1941}}\n{{chart|aa943|:|:| 5AR | | |!| |5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), CAC, CASF</small>|aa943=1943}}\n{{chart|aa945|:|:| 5AR | | |!| |5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), RCAC, CASF</small>|aa945=1945}}\n{{chart|aa946|:|:|Dbndd| | |!| |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa946=1946}}\n{{chart|aa949|:|:| | | | | 8PLH|8PLH=8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars <small>(5th Armd Regt)</small>|aa949=1949}}\n{{chart|aa957|:|:| 18CH| | 28CH|28CH=2/8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|18CH=1/8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|aa957=1957}}\n{{chart|aa960|:|:|8CHPL| |CHPLM|aa960=1960|8CHPL=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|CHPLM=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's) (Militia)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa960|:|L| P6R |~| P6R |aa960=1960|P6R=''Perpetuates 6th Regt''}}\n{{chart|aa993|:| | |`| 8CH |'| |aa993=1993|8CH=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa012|L|~|~|~|PW181| | |aa012=2012|PW181=''Perpetuates War of 1812 units''}}\n{{chart|CrntY| | | | | |!| | | |CrntY={{CURRENTYEAR}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\n{{(!}}class=\"wikitable\"\n{{!}}+ Abbreviations used in the chart\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} '''Abbreviation''' {{!!}} '''Phrase'''\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Armd {{!!}} Armoured\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Bn {{!!}} Battalion\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CAC {{!!}} [[Canadian Armoured Corps]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CASF {{!!}} [[Canadian Active Service Force]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Cavy {{!!}} Cavalry\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CEF {{!!}} [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} RCAC {{!!}} [[Royal Canadian Armoured Corps]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Regt {{!!}} Regiment\n{{!)}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[Image:8CH guidon.jpg|thumb|The Guidon of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's).]]\n\nIn the list below, battle honours in capitals were awarded for participation in large operations and campaigns, while those in lowercase indicate honours granted for more specific battles. Those battle honours followed by a \"+\" are emblazoned on the regimental [[Guidon (Commonwealth)|guidon]].<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The War of 1812===\n*Honorary Distinction: the non-emblazonable honorary distinction DEFENCE OF CANADA \u2013 1812-1815 \u2013 D\u00c9FENSE DU CANADA.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/westernfront/mountsorrel.htm MOUNT SORREL]}} 2\u201313 June 1916+\n*{{smallcaps|[[Battle of the Somme|SOMME, 1916]]}} 1 July-18 November 1916+\n*{{smallcaps|[[Western Front (World War I)|FRANCE AND FLANDERS, 1915-16]]}}+)<ref name=Vol3/><ref name=\"canadiansoldiers.com\">http://www.canadiansoldiers.com CanadianSoldiers.com accessed 12 August 2014</ref>\n\n===The Second World War===\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/italiancampaign/lirivalley.htm LIRI VALLEY]}} 18\u201330 May 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance to Rome|Melfa Crossing]] 24\u201325 May 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance to Rome|Ceprano]] 26\u201327 May 1944\n*{{smallcaps|[[Gothic Line|GOTHIC LINE]]}} 25 August-22 September 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Montecchio]] 30\u201331 August 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Tomba di Pesaro]] 1\u20132 September 1944\n*{{smallcaps|[[Gothic Line|LAMONE CROSSING]]}} 2\u201313 September 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Coriano]] 3\u201315 September 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance into Northern Italy|Misano Ridge]]\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Conventello-Comacchio]] 2\u20136 January 1945\n*{{smallcaps|[[Italian Campaign (World War II)|ITALY, 1944-1945]]}}\n*[[Western Allied invasion of Germany|IJsselmeer]] 15\u201318 April 1945\n*[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/northwesteurope/delfzijlpocket.htm Delfzijl Pocket] 23 April-2 May 1945\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/campaigns/northwesteurope/northwesteurope.htm NORTH-WEST EUROPE, 1945]}}<ref name=Vol3 /><ref name=\"canadiansoldiers.com\"/>\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{smallcaps|Afghanistan}}<ref name=\"pm.gc.ca\"/>\n\n==8th Hussars Regimental Museum==\n{{Infobox museum\n|name       = 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) Museum\n|image      = SussexStationStreetside.jpg\n|established=\n|location   = former train station in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]]  [[Kings County, New Brunswick|Kings]] [[New Brunswick]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|45.7225|-65.5128|type:landmark_region:CA|display=inline}}\n|website    = [http://8chassociation.com/Museum.html 8th Hussars Regimental Museum]\n}}\nThe regiment's museum is located in a former train station in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]].  Exhibits focus on the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) military history and activities, and include uniforms, medals, weapons and artifacts from different wars.\n\n==Perpetuations==\n===War of 1812===\n*1st Battalion, [[Westmorland County Regiment]]\n*2nd Battalion, Westmorland County Regiment)<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\n*[[6th Regiment Canadian Mounted Rifles, CEF]]<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n==Alliances==\n*{{GBR}} - [[Queen's Royal Hussars|The Queen's Royal Hussars (Queen's Own and Royal Irish)]]\n*{{GBR}} - [[Queen's Own Yorkshire Yeomanry|Yorkshire Yeomanry]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|War}}\n* [[The Canadian Crown and the Canadian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20070426034135/http://www.8chassociation.com/Regiment1.html\n*{{citation |url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par1/index-eng.asp  |series=Canadian Forces Publication |title=A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. |volume=Volume 3: Part 1 Armour, Artillery and Field Engineer Regiments}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''The 8th Hussars: A History of the Regiment'', Sussex, NB: Maritime Publishing, 1964 by [[Douglas How]].\n* ''The 8th (Eighth) Hussars (Princess Louise's) 1962-1987'' by Major G.H. - Editor-In-Chief; Lawson, Captain R.J. - Editor MacDonald (1987)\n* ''New Brunswick Hussar: Corporal Harold Jorgen Skaarup, G753, 5th Armored Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick'' by Harold A. Skaarup (Jul 1 2001)\n* ''A Century of Rifles 1860 - 1960. The Halifax Rifles (R.C.A.C) (M) 'Cede Nullis''' by John Gordon Quigley (Jan 1 1960)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/8-canadian-hussars/index.page 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) Official Home Page]\n* [http://www.8chassociation.com/Museum.html] 8th Hussars Regimental Museum\n* [http://www.militaryheritage.com/8thhussars.htm History and Uniform of the 8th Canadian (Princess Louise's) Hussars, 1848 to 1970]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{order of precedence\n | before= [[The Halifax Rifles (RCAC)]]\n | title=  8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n | after= [[The Ontario Regiment (RCAC)]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Royal Canadian Armoured Corps Regiments}}\n{{Canadian Armed Forces}}\n{{Worthington Trophy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Armoured regiments of Canada]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1848]]\n[[Category:Hussars]]\n[[Category:Cavalry regiments of Canada]]\n[[Category:British colonial regiments]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Canada in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n| image=8th Canadian Hussars Princess Louises badge.jpg\n| image_size = 150\n|caption= Regimental [[cap badge]]\n|dates= 1869\u2013present\n|country= Canada\n|branch= [[Canadian Army]]\n|type= Armoured Reconnaissance\n|role= Reconnaissance\n|size=\n|command_structure=[[37 Canadian Brigade Group]]\n|garrison=[[Moncton]]\n|garrison_label=\n|ceremonial_chief=[[Anne, Princess Royal]]\n|ceremonial_chief_label=Colonel-in-chief\n|nickname=The Crazy Eights\n|patron=[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll]]\n|motto={{lang-la|Regi patriaeque fidelis|lit=Faithful to king and country}}\n|colors=\n|colors_label=\n|march=\"The 8th Hussars\"\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|identification_symbol = VIII CH\n|identification_symbol_label = Abbreviation\n}}\nThe '''8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)''' (VIII CH) is the longest-serving armoured [[regiment]] in the [[Canadian Army]]. It was formed on the 4 April 1848 in New Brunswick where it has served continually ever since. Today it is a reserve armoured reconnaissance regiment with 2 Squadrons. Its Regimental Headquarters (RHQ)and A Squadron are located in [[Moncton]] with B Squadron located in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]].\n\nIn 1957 its name was chosen for the formation of a new Regular Force regiment to serve in addition to the reserve regiment. The Regular regiment served in [[CFB Gagetown|Gagetown]], New Brunswick, Petawawa, Ontario, the Sinai, Cyprus, Iserlohn (Fort Beausejour), Soest and Lahr, West Germany. The Regular Force regiment was disbanded in 1998. The reserve regiment of the VIII CH remains.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest beginnings of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) have traditionally been traced to the year 1775 in the Colony of Virginia where Captain John Saunders, of Princess Anne County, raised a troop of cavalry at his own expense to fight for the Crown against the Colonial rebels. This unusual Regiment included riflemen, grenadiers, artillery and cavalry, and it never knew defeat during the American conflict for independence. In September 1783, the Regiment as an entity sailed for Nova Scotia and reached Saint John on 27 September 1783. A large number of these Loyalists soldiers settled in the Saint John and Kennebecasis valleys by Loyalist soldiers, had a military tradition and indeed an effective militia. In 1839, the York County Troop, known for a time as the York Light Dragoons, was mobilized for service in the Aroostook War, a conflict with American lumbermen that never quite came to open fighting. For four months they patrolled the border and roads between Woodstock, Fredericton and Saint John. By 1848, eleven troops of cavalry were in existence. These troops included Hampton Troop of Cavalry, Assekeag Troop of Cavalry, Apohaqui Troop of Cavalry, Upham Troop of Cavalry, Johnston Troop of Cavalry, Shediac Troop of Cavalry, Springfield Troop of Cavalry, among others.\n\nBy authority of Militia General Order No 1 of 4 April 1848, these eleven independent troops were united to form a Regiment entitled the New Brunswick Yeomanry Cavalry. It is this date that is officially recognized as the formation date of the 8th Canadian Hussars.\n*Redesignated 31 May 1872 as the 8th Regiment of Cavalry\n*Redesignated 18 July 1884 as the 8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick Regiment of Cavalry\n*Redesignated 1 January 1893 8th \"Princess Louise's New Brunswick Hussars\"\n*Redesignated 11 February 1941 as the 2nd (Reserve) Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars\n*Redesignated 1 April 1941 as the 5th (Reserve) Armoured Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars\n*Redesignated 4 February 1949 as the 8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars (5th Armoured Regiment)\n*Redesignated 29 January 1957 as the 2/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) upon the formation of the Canadian Army (Regular) 1/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n*1 January 1960 the 2/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were redesignated as 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) (Militia) and the 1/8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were redesignated as the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n*15 April 1993 the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) (Militia) and the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) were amalgamated and redesignated as the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)<ref name=Vol3>Canadian Forces Publication A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. Volume 3: Combat Arms Regiments.</ref>\n\n===South African War===\n[[Image:8CH camp flag.jpg|thumb|The camp flag of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's).]]The regiment contributed volunteers for the Canadian Contingents that served in South Africa.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\nThe 6th Regiment, Canadian Mounted Rifles Battalion, CEF, was authorized on 7 November 1914 and embarked for England on 17 July 1915. It disembarked in France on 24 October 1915, where it continued to train until 2 January 1916 when its personnel were absorbed by the [[4th Battalion, Canadian Mounted Rifles]] and the [[5th Battalion, Canadian Mounted Rifles, CEF]]. The regiment disbanded on 18 February 1918.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Second World War===\nThe Second World War provided the regiment's first opportunity for active service as a formed unit. The regiment mobilized as the 4th Canadian Motorcycle Regiment, CASF (8 NBH) on 24 May 1940. It was converted to armour and redesignated as the \"8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars) CAC, CASF\", on 9 February 1941; as the 5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, CASF, on 11 February 1941.\nThe regiment embarked for Britain on 9 October 1941\n\nThe regiment landed in Italy on 19 December 1943 as a unit of the 5th Armoured Brigade, [[5th Canadian Armoured Division]]. It was renamed as the \"5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, CAC, CASF\", on 15 October 1943.\nThe regiment [[Allied invasion of Italy|landed in Italy]] on 19 December 1943 at Naples and saw action soon and frequently thereafter. The regiment fought in the Liri Valley, the Melfa Crossing, Ceprano, The Gothic Line, Missano Ridge, Coriano, the [[Lamone (river)|Lamone River]] Crossing, and Coventello where it distinguished itself.\n\nIt moved to North-West Europe on 17 February 1945 as part of [[Operation Goldflake]]. The Hussars sailed from Italy to Southern France, and then moved by rail to Northwest Europe. After refitting the tanks, the regiment went into action in the Netherlands, breaking through to Putten in mid-April. The regiment then moved north for the final actions of the war at the Delfzijl Pocket where 3,000 German soldiers surrendered to the regiment. It was renamed as the \"5th Armoured Regiment (8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars, RCAC, CASF\", on 2 August 1945.\n\nOn 26 January 1946, the regiment arrived in Halifax and the next day reached Sussex, New Brunswick where it was demobilized. The overseas regiment disbanded on 15 February 1946.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===Post World War II===\nIn 1950, the regiment was called upon to provide men for service with the Special Force which was raised and deployed to Korea, and in 1951 \"Y\" Troop was organized for service with the 27th Canadian Infantry Brigade in Germany.\n\nOn 29 January 1957, it was decided that a third armoured regiment would be formed in the [[Land Force Command|Canadian Army]]. As a result, the regiment was honoured with the privilege of providing its name to the new regiment. This resulted in the change of the regiment's name to the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's). The Regular Regiment served in [[CFB Gagetown|Gagetown]], New Brunswick, Petawawa, Ontario, the Sinai, Cyprus, Iserlohn (Fort Beausejour), Soest and Lahr, West Germany.\n\nCpl. Paul R. Wallace and Tpr. Adrian A. Bons died while deployed to the Sinai as part of the United Nations Emergency Force on 27 November 1964.\n\nIn the summer of 1965, the regiment was deployed from their base at [[Petawawa, Ontario]] on a peacekeeping mission for the United Nations to the island nation of Cyprus. Tpr. Lennard W. Nass died on 27 September 1966 while deployed to Cyprus as part of the United Nations Force in Cyprus.\n\nThe regiment has participated in several \"aid to the civil authority\" missions in recent history. In the summer of 1990 the regiment sent a troop sized force to the province of Quebec in Cougars to assist in Canadian Forces Operations in the [[Oka Crisis]]. In the [[1998 Ice Storm]], the regiment provided a platoon-sized force to assist in the maintenance of infrastructure in the community of [[St. George, New Brunswick]]. In the fall of 1998, the regiment provided soldiers to the recovery effort for Swiss Air Flight 111.\n\nIn 2004, 8CH became an armoured reconnaissance unit, in place of its previous designation as simply an armoured unit. Along with this trade change the unit was given the new [[Mercedes-Benz]] [[Mercedes-Benz G-Class|G-Wagon]], a Jeep-like vehicle more suited to their new role as reconnaissance. The unit is stationed at the Moncton and Sussex detachments of [[CFB Gagetown]], [[New Brunswick]]. Its [[Colonel-in-Chief]] is [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]].\n\n===War in Afghanistan===\nThe regiment contributed an aggregate of more than 20% of its authorized strength to the various Task Forces which served in Afghanistan between 2002 and 2014.<ref name=\"pm.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2014/05/09/south-west-asia-theatre-honours |title=South-West Asia Theatre Honours |accessdate=2014-05-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231549/http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2014/05/09/south-west-asia-theatre-honours |archivedate=2014-05-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Lineage chart===\nLineage of the units of the 8th Canadian Hussars:<ref>{{cite web|title=8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)|url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par1/arm-bli/8CH-eng.asp|website=Volume 3, Part 1: Armour, Artillery and Field Engineer Regiments \u2013 Armour Regiments|publisher=Directorate of History and Heritage|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n{{chart top|width=100%|Lineage}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|aa812| | |12WCR| | | | |aa812=1812|12WCR=1st and 2nd Bn, Westmorland County Regt}}\n{{chart|aa815|F|~|Dbndd| | | | |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa815=1815}}\n{{chart|aa864|:| | | | | |Ippvy|Ippvy=Independent troops of cavy|aa864=1864}}\n{{chart|aa869|:| | | | | | NBYC|aa869=1869|NBYC=New Brunswick Regt of Yeomanry Cavy}}\n{{chart|aa872|:| | | | | |8Cavy|aa872=1872|8Cavy=8th Regt of Cavy}}\n{{chart|aa884|:| | | | | |8PLNB|8PLNB=8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick Regt of Cavy|aa884=1884}}\n{{chart|aa893|:| | | | | |8PLNB|8PLNB=8th <small>\"Princess Louise's New Brunswick Hussars\"</small>|aa893=1893}}\n{{chart|aa914|:| | 6CMR| | |!| |6CMR=6th Regt, Canadian Mounted Rifles, <small>CEF</small>|aa914=1914}}\n{{chart|aa916|:| |A45CM| | |!| |A45CM=''Absorbed by 4th and 5th Canadian Mounted Rifles Bn, <small>CEF</small>''|aa916=1916}}\n{{chart|aa918|:|F|Dbndd| | |!| |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa918=1918}}\n{{chart| nbsp|:|:| | | | | |!| |nbsp=&nbsp;}}\n{{chart|aa940|:|:| 4CMR| | |!| |aa940=1940|4CMR=4th Canadian Motorcycle Regt, <small>CASF (8 NBH)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa941|:|:| 8PLH| |28PLH|28PLH=2nd <small>(Reserve)</small> Regt, 8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars|8PLH=8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars, <small>CAC, CASF</small>|aa941=1941}}\n{{chart|aa941|:|:| 5AR | |5A8PL|5A8PL=5th <small>(Reserve)</small> Armd Regt, 8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars|5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), CASF</small>|aa941=1941}}\n{{chart|aa943|:|:| 5AR | | |!| |5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), CAC, CASF</small>|aa943=1943}}\n{{chart|aa945|:|:| 5AR | | |!| |5AR=5th Armd Regt <small>(8th Princess Louise's (New Brunswick) Hussars), RCAC, CASF</small>|aa945=1945}}\n{{chart|aa946|:|:|Dbndd| | |!| |Dbndd=''Disbanded''|aa946=1946}}\n{{chart|aa949|:|:| | | | | 8PLH|8PLH=8th Princess Louise's <small>(New Brunswick)</small> Hussars <small>(5th Armd Regt)</small>|aa949=1949}}\n{{chart|aa957|:|:| 18CH| | 28CH|28CH=2/8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|18CH=1/8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|aa957=1957}}\n{{chart|aa960|:|:|8CHPL| |CHPLM|aa960=1960|8CHPL=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>|CHPLM=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's) (Militia)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa960|:|L| P6R |~| P6R |aa960=1960|P6R=''Perpetuates 6th Regt''}}\n{{chart|aa993|:| | |`| 8CH |'| |aa993=1993|8CH=8th Canadian Hussars <small>(Princess Louise's)</small>}}\n{{chart|aa012|L|~|~|~|PW181| | |aa012=2012|PW181=''Perpetuates War of 1812 units''}}\n{{chart|CrntY| | | | | |!| | | |CrntY={{CURRENTYEAR}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\n{{(!}}class=\"wikitable\"\n{{!}}+ Abbreviations used in the chart\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} '''Abbreviation''' {{!!}} '''Phrase'''\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Armd {{!!}} Armoured\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Bn {{!!}} Battalion\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CAC {{!!}} [[Canadian Armoured Corps]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CASF {{!!}} [[Canadian Active Service Force]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Cavy {{!!}} Cavalry\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} CEF {{!!}} [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} RCAC {{!!}} [[Royal Canadian Armoured Corps]]\n{{!}}-\n{{!}} Regt {{!!}} Regiment\n{{!)}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[Image:8CH guidon.jpg|thumb|The Guidon of the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's).]]\n\nIn the list below, battle honours in capitals were awarded for participation in large operations and campaigns, while those in lowercase indicate honours granted for more specific battles. Those battle honours followed by a \"+\" are emblazoned on the regimental [[Guidon (Commonwealth)|guidon]].<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The War of 1812===\n*Honorary Distinction: the non-emblazonable honorary distinction DEFENCE OF CANADA \u2013 1812-1815 \u2013 D\u00c9FENSE DU CANADA.<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/westernfront/mountsorrel.htm MOUNT SORREL]}} 2\u201313 June 1916+\n*{{smallcaps|[[Battle of the Somme|SOMME, 1916]]}} 1 July-18 November 1916+\n*{{smallcaps|[[Western Front (World War I)|FRANCE AND FLANDERS, 1915-16]]}}+)<ref name=Vol3/><ref name=\"canadiansoldiers.com\">http://www.canadiansoldiers.com CanadianSoldiers.com accessed 12 August 2014</ref>\n\n===The Second World War===\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/italiancampaign/lirivalley.htm LIRI VALLEY]}} 18\u201330 May 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance to Rome|Melfa Crossing]] 24\u201325 May 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance to Rome|Ceprano]] 26\u201327 May 1944\n*{{smallcaps|[[Gothic Line|GOTHIC LINE]]}} 25 August-22 September 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Montecchio]] 30\u201331 August 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Tomba di Pesaro]] 1\u20132 September 1944\n*{{smallcaps|[[Gothic Line|LAMONE CROSSING]]}} 2\u201313 September 1944\n*[[Gothic Line|Coriano]] 3\u201315 September 1944\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)#Allied advance into Northern Italy|Misano Ridge]]\n*[[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Conventello-Comacchio]] 2\u20136 January 1945\n*{{smallcaps|[[Italian Campaign (World War II)|ITALY, 1944-1945]]}}\n*[[Western Allied invasion of Germany|IJsselmeer]] 15\u201318 April 1945\n*[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/battlehonours/northwesteurope/delfzijlpocket.htm Delfzijl Pocket] 23 April-2 May 1945\n*{{smallcaps|[http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/campaigns/northwesteurope/northwesteurope.htm NORTH-WEST EUROPE, 1945]}}<ref name=Vol3 /><ref name=\"canadiansoldiers.com\"/>\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{smallcaps|Afghanistan}}<ref name=\"pm.gc.ca\"/>\n\n==8th Hussars Regimental Museum==\n{{Infobox museum\n|name       = 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) Museum\n|image      = SussexStationStreetside.jpg\n|established=\n|location   = former train station in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]]  [[Kings County, New Brunswick|Kings]] [[New Brunswick]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|45.7225|-65.5128|type:landmark_region:CA|display=inline}}\n|website    = [http://8chassociation.com/Museum.html 8th Hussars Regimental Museum]\n}}\nThe regiment's museum is located in a former train station in [[Sussex, New Brunswick]].  Exhibits focus on the 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) military history and activities, and include uniforms, medals, weapons and artifacts from different wars.\n\n==Perpetuations==\n===War of 1812===\n*1st Battalion, [[Westmorland County Regiment]]\n*2nd Battalion, Westmorland County Regiment)<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n===The Great War===\n*[[6th Regiment Canadian Mounted Rifles, CEF]]<ref name=Vol3/>\n\n==Alliances==\n*{{GBR}} - [[Queen's Royal Hussars|The Queen's Royal Hussars (Queen's Own and Royal Irish)]]\n*{{GBR}} - [[Queen's Own Yorkshire Yeomanry|Yorkshire Yeomanry]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|War}}\n* [[The Canadian Crown and the Canadian Forces]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20070426034135/http://www.8chassociation.com/Regiment1.html\n*{{citation |url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/ol-lo/vol-tom-3/par1/index-eng.asp  |series=Canadian Forces Publication |title=A-DH-267-003 Insignia and Lineages of the Canadian Forces. |volume=Volume 3: Part 1 Armour, Artillery and Field Engineer Regiments}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''The 8th Hussars: A History of the Regiment'', Sussex, NB: Maritime Publishing, 1964 by [[Douglas How]].\n* ''The 8th (Eighth) Hussars (Princess Louise's) 1962-1987'' by Major G.H. - Editor-In-Chief; Lawson, Captain R.J. - Editor MacDonald (1987)\n* ''New Brunswick Hussar: Corporal Harold Jorgen Skaarup, G753, 5th Armored Regiment, 8th Princess Louise's New Brunswick'' by Harold A. Skaarup (Jul 1 2001)\n* ''A Century of Rifles 1860 - 1960. The Halifax Rifles (R.C.A.C) (M) 'Cede Nullis''' by John Gordon Quigley (Jan 1 1960)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/8-canadian-hussars/index.page 8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's) Official Home Page]\n* [http://www.8chassociation.com/Museum.html] 8th Hussars Regimental Museum\n* [http://www.militaryheritage.com/8thhussars.htm History and Uniform of the 8th Canadian (Princess Louise's) Hussars, 1848 to 1970]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{order of precedence\n | before= [[The Halifax Rifles (RCAC)]]\n | title=  8th Canadian Hussars (Princess Louise's)\n | after= [[The Ontario Regiment (RCAC)]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Royal Canadian Armoured Corps Regiments}}\n{{Canadian Armed Forces}}\n{{Worthington Trophy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Armoured regiments of Canada]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1848]]\n[[Category:Hussars]]\n[[Category:Cavalry regiments of Canada]]\n[[Category:British colonial regiments]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Canada in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Cjrother", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8th_Canadian_Hussars_(Princess_Louise%27s)"}
{"title_page": "Madden NFL", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game series\n| title = Madden NFL\n| image = EA Sports Madden NFL logo (no year).png\n| caption = ''Madden NFL'' series logo\n| genre = [[American football|American football video game]]\n| developer = [[EA Tiburon]]\n| publisher = [[EA Sports]]\n| platforms = [[Personal computer|PC]], [[Commodore Amiga]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], [[Sega Genesis|Genesis]], [[Game Gear]], [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]], [[Nintendo 64]], [[GameCube]], [[Wii]], [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Game Boy]], [[Game Boy Color]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], [[DOS]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Portable]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[Sega Saturn]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]], [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[BlackBerry PlayBook]], [[Arcade game|arcade]]\n| first release version = ''[[John Madden Football (1988 video game)|John Madden Football]]''\n| first release date = June 1, 1988\n| latest release version = ''Madden NFL 20'' \n| latest release date = 2020  \n}}\n\n'''''Madden NFL''''' (known as ''John Madden Football'' until 1993) is an [[American football]] [[video game]] series developed by [[EA Tiburon]] for [[EA Sports]]. It is named after [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] coach and commentator [[John Madden]], and has sold more than 130 million copies. It also currently is the only officially licensed [[National Football League]] (NFL) video game, and has influenced many players and coaches of the physical sport. Among the game's features are detailed playbooks and player statistics, and voice commentary in the style of a real [[National Football League on television|NFL television broadcast]]. {{asof|2013}} the franchise has generated over $4 billion in sales.\n\n[[Electronic Arts]] (EA) founder [[Trip Hawkins]] conceived the series and approached Madden in 1984 for his endorsement and expertise. Because of Madden's insistence that the game be as realistic as possible, the first version of ''John Madden Football'' did not appear until 1988. EA has released annual versions since 1990, and the series' name changed to ''Madden NFL'' in 1993 after EA acquired the rights to use NFL teams and players. Madden retired as a broadcaster in 2009, but continues to lend his name and to provide expertise for the game franchise.\n\n==Overview==\n{{rquote|right|A computer is a helluva lot smarter than me.|John Madden, 2014{{r|helfand20150202}}}}\n\n{{as of|2013}} Electronic Arts has sold more than 100 million copies of ''Madden NFL'', and more than five million in one year, for more than $4 billion in total sales.<ref name=\"gaudiosi20130905\">{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/09/05/technology/innovation/madden-25/ | title=Madden: The $4 billion video game franchise | work=CNN | date=2013-09-05 | accessdate=25 January 2015 | author=Gaudiosi, John}}</ref> At [[EA Tiburon]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] a team of 30 developers and more than 100 [[game testers]] works on each new game in the series,<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/> which {{asof|2012|alt=as of 2012}} contains more than 10 million lines of [[source code]].<ref name=\"bissell20120117\">{{cite news | url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/7473139/tom-bissell-making-madden-nfl | title=Kickoff: ''Madden NFL'' and the Future of Video Game Sports | work=Grantland | date=2012-01-17 | accessdate=January 21, 2012 | author=Bissell, Tom}}</ref>\n\nMadden, once better known for [[Ace Hardware]] commercials than football despite winning [[Super Bowl XI]] as the head coach for the [[History of the Oakland Raiders|Oakland Raiders]], is now better known for ''Madden NFL'' than as coach or broadcaster.<ref name=\"horowitz20071123\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sega-16.com/2007/11/interview-michael-knox/ | title=Interview: Michael Knox | publisher=Sega-16 | date=2007-11-23 | accessdate=25 January 2015 | author=Horowitz, Ken}}</ref>{{r|thefranchise}} He receives an estimated $2 to 3 million each year for his endorsement<ref name=\"snider20080806\">{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2008-08-05-madden-game-main_N.htm | title=As John Madden would say, 'Boom!' His NFL game turns 20 | work=USA Today | date=2008-08-06 | accessdate=25 January 2015 | author=Snider, Mike}}</ref> but describes himself as \"never a good player\" of ''Madden'', and prefers to watch others play.{{r|bissell20120117}} Although Madden says that \"a computer is a helluva lot smarter than me\"{{r|helfand20150202}} he has influenced the series' design from the first game, and since retiring from broadcasting and doing videogame voice commentary in 2009 his participation in each ''Madden''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s development has increased:{{r|bissell20120117}}<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>\n{{quote|He breaks down upcoming rules changes. He brings up concussions, helmet-to-helmet hits and gimmick quarterbacks. A digression on how the [[Dome Patrol]]-era [[New Orleans Saints|Saints]] used to frustrate [[Bill Walsh (American football coach)|Bill Walsh]]'s [[San Francisco 49ers|49ers]] teams with short linebacker drops becomes a lecture on the obsolescence of the fullback, which then morphs into a short aside on player character.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>}}\n\n{{rquote|right|Madden recalls a time in San Francisco when a [[Philadelphia Eagles]] player rushed into a hotel room asking, 'Where's Madden?' When people pointed to the [[Fox NFL|Fox]] commentator, the player said, 'No, not that Madden. I want the game!'|''Los Angeles Times'', 2002{{r|pham20020131}}}}\nEA estimates that the series has five to seven million dedicated fans, and an underground circuit of ''Madden'' cash tournaments exists.{{r|bissell20120117}} [[Marshall Faulk]] in 2010 estimated that \"50 percent on up\" of NFL players are ''Madden'' players, who play in the league with or against childhood heroes they once chose to play as in the game.{{r|suellentrop20100125}} Players typically play as themselves regardless of their electronic counterparts' abilities<ref name=\"pham20020131\">{{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jan/31/news/tt-madden31 | title=Odds-On Favorite | work=Los Angeles Times | date=2002-01-31 | accessdate=January 21, 2012 | author=Pham, Alex}}</ref><ref name=\"yoon20110608\">{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/los-angeles/nfl/news/story?id=6635659 | title=Alterraun Verner's lockout to-do list | publisher=ESPN | date=2011-06-08 | accessdate=14 November 2013 | author=Yoon, Peter}}</ref>{{r|suellentrop20100125}} and immediately check new releases of the game for changes in the more than 60 ratings of their talent.<ref name=\"mcclusky20030813\">{{cite news | url=http://archive.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/news/2003/08/59991?currentPage=all | title=Madden Keeps Gaining Ground | work=Wired | date=2003-08-13 | accessdate=23 January 2015 | author=McClusky, Mark}}</ref><ref name=\"helfand20150202\">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-madden-super-bowl-20150203-story.html | title=In a first, Madden NFL accurately predicts score for Super Bowl XLIX | work=Los Angeles Times | date=2015-02-02 | accessdate=2 February 2015 | author=Helfand, Zach}}</ref> They often complain to Madden and EA about allegedly inaccurate ratings (only [[Emmitt Smith]] has told him that the game rated him too high), or ask for changes in their [[avatar (computing)|in-game appearance]]. Such complaints began as early as 1990, confusing the broadcaster, who did not contribute the player statistics for that year's version due to lack of time.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>{{r|snider20080806}}\n\nCoaches and players at all levels of the sport say that ''Madden'' has influenced them, and recommend the game to learn football strategy and tactics, practice plays and assignments, and simulate opponents.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>{{r|suellentrop20100125}} Young players who grew up with it reportedly understand plays better than those who did not. ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' in 2010 wrote that the growing use of rookie quarterbacks and the [[spread offense]] was influenced by the game, stating that \"the sport is being taken over by something you might call Maddenball \u2014 a sophisticated, high-scoring, pass-happy, youth-driven phenomenon\". When the [[Denver Broncos]]' [[Brandon Stokley]] in 2009 burned six seconds of the clock with an unusual run before scoring the winning touchdown against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], ''Madden'' designers\u2014who were watching the game with Madden\u2014immediately recognized his action as \"what happens in the game!\"<ref name=\"suellentrop20100125\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/2010/01/ff_gamechanger/all/ | title=Game Changers: How Videogames Trained a Generation of Athletes | work=Wired | date=2010-01-25 | accessdate=22 January 2015 | author=Suellentrop, Chris}}</ref>{{r|thefranchise}}\n\n[[National Football League on television|Football broadcasts on television]] use ''Madden''-like visual cues to more closely resemble it, and the NFL considers the series its \"33rd franchise\" because each week during the season EA Sports receives the same searchable film database of every play that each of the league's 32 teams do.{{r|thefranchise}}{{r|bissell20120117}}{{r|helfand20150202}} The game is the NFL's second-largest source of licensing revenue after apparel, and an important part of the league's recruitment of children as new football fans.{{r|pham20020131}}\n\nThe [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2003 opened an interactive exhibit in which visitors play ''Madden'',{{r|mcclusky20030813}} three years before its namesake's induction.{{r|thefranchise}} [[Museum of the Moving Image (New York City)|Museum of the Moving Image]] in New York City in early 2014 celebrated ''Madden NFL''{{'}}s 25th anniversary, with an exhibit including five playable versions of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/1/8/5287758/madden-nfl-25-years-exhibit-museum-of-the-moving-image|title=Museum of the Moving Image looks back on 25 years of Madden|last=Tach|first=Dave|date=8 January 2014|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a similar approach used by the automobile industry, until ''Madden NFL 25'', the ''Madden'' series has always historically been numbered one year later than the year in which it is released. However, the season it represents is the year in which the game is released (thus, ''[[Madden NFL 13]]'' was actually released in 2012 and is modeled after the [[2012 NFL season]]).\n\n===Voice commentary===\nVoice commentary in ''Madden'' allows players or watchers to hear the game being called as if it were a real game on [[television|TV]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Adams | first = Ernest | title = Putting Madden in Madden: Memoirs of an EA Sports Video Producer | website = [[Gamasutra]] | date = 2002-04-26 | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/features/20020427/adams_01.htm | accessdate = 2009-05-15}}</ref> For early versions of the game, this commentary was performed by Madden himself and his play-by-play partner. Initially, this was [[Pat Summerall]], his partner during their days at [[NFL on CBS|CBS]] and [[Fox NFL|Fox]] from the early 1980s to the early 2000s until Summerall retired; the role was then filled by [[Al Michaels]], John's broadcast partner on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' ([[2002 NFL season|2002]]\u2013[[2005 NFL season|2005]]) and ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football]]'' ([[2006 NFL season|2006]]\u2013[[2008 NFL season|2008]]). For the first Madden games on the [[Xbox 360]] and [[PS3]], they featured a generic EA Sports radio announcer doing play-by-play. This started with ''[[Madden NFL 06|Madden 06]]'' and ended with ''[[Madden NFL 08|Madden 08]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/madden-nfl-06-review/1900-6140115/|title=Madden NFL 06 Review|first=Alex|last=Navarro|date=18 November 2005|publisher=}}</ref> Other versions of those games still featured Madden's commentary.\n\n''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' would end up being the last version to feature Madden's commentary, albeit in a reduced role. By that time, he felt that reciting a script covering every single scenario in the game was boring and tedious<ref name=\"markazi20090821\"/>&mdash;Madden recalled the long hours spent alone in the recording studio as \"the most difficult part of any part that I've ever had in the game and the least amount of fun\"{{r|bissell20120117}}&mdash;but said that in the decision to remove him from game commentary, \"I feel that something is being taken away from me\".<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>\n\nMadden and Michaels were replaced by [[Cris Collinsworth]] as color commentator and [[Tom Hammond]] on play-by-play in ''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' and ''[[Madden NFL 10]]''. [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]] replaced Hammond in ''[[Madden NFL 11]]'' and ''[[Madden NFL 12]]'', with Collinsworth handling color commentary in both games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robinson|first=Jon|title=Gus Johnson joins 'Madden NFL 11' booth|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/thelife/videogames/blog/_/name/thegamer/id/5207709/gus-johnson-joins-madden-nfl-11-booth|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=May 21, 2010|access-date=May 22, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Madden NFL 13]]'' marked the debut of real-life announcing team [[Jim Nantz]] and [[Phil Simms]], including them appearing in an in-booth cutscene before the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Madden NFL 13 Features: Presentation |url=http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/feature/presentation |publisher=EA Sports |accessdate=2012-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427215638/http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/feature/presentation |archivedate=2012-04-27 }}</ref> Nantz and Simms stayed until ''[[Madden NFL 16]]'', when they were replaced by [[Fox NFL|Fox]]'s [[Brandon Gaudin]] and [[Charles Davis (defensive back)|Charles Davis]] for ''[[Madden NFL 17]]''. Nantz continued to work as the primary play-by-play announcer for [[NFL on CBS|CBS]], while Simms would later leave the CBS broadcast booth to work on ''[[The NFL Today]]''. Gaudin and Davis returned to the studio throughout the [[2016 NFL season]] to add new commentary relevant to each week of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news/2016/madden-17-commentary-team|title=Madden 17 Commentary Team|website=EA SPORTS}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, ''Madden NFL 08'' and ''Madden NFL 09'' were also released in Spanish, featuring [[ESPN Deportes]] announcer [[\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn (sports announcer)|\u00c1lvaro Mart\u00edn]] providing both play-by-play and analysis.<ref>[https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/09/16/madden-nfl-09-en-espaaol-ships-to-retailers-today Madden NFL 09 en Espa\u00f1ol ships to retailers today] - IGN, 16 September 2008</ref>\n\n===Series overview===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Titles in the series\n|-\n! Title\n! Release year\n! PC\n! [[History of video game consoles (fourth generation)|4th generation]]\n! [[History of video game consoles (fifth generation)|5th generation]]\n! [[History of video game consoles (sixth generation)|6th generation]]\n! [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|7th generation]]\n! [[History of video game consoles (eighth generation)|8th generation]]\n! [[Mobile device|Handheld]]\n! Other platforms\n! Notes\n! On the cover\n|-\n| ''[[John Madden Football (1988 video game)|John Madden Football]]'' || 1988 || [[MS-DOS]] || || || || || || || [[Commodore 64|C=64]]/[[Commodore 128|C=128]], [[Apple II]] || || [[John Madden]]\n|-\n| ''[[John Madden Football (1990 video game)|John Madden Football]]'' || 1990 || || [[Sega Genesis|Genesis]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] || || || || || || [[Amiga]] || || John Madden\n|-\n| ''[[John Madden Football II]]'' || 1991 || MS-DOS