PS2 || Xbox 360, PS3, Wii || || PSP, iOS || || || [[Drew Brees]] of the [[New Orleans Saints]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL Football]]'' || 2011 || || || || || || || [[Nintendo 3DS|3DS]] || || || ''Madden NFL Football'' logo\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 12]]'' || 2011 || || || || PS2 || Xbox 360, PS3, Wii || || PSP, iOS, [[Android (operating system)|Android]], BlackBerry Playbook || || || [[Peyton Hillis]] of the [[Cleveland Browns]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 13]]'' || 2012 || || || || || Xbox 360, PS3, Wii || [[Wii U]] || [[PlayStation Vita|PS Vita]], iOS || || || [[Calvin Johnson]] of the [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 25]]'' || 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news/article/madden-25-release-date|title=Madden NFL 25 Demo Now Available|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> || || || || || Xbox 360, PS3  || [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4|PS4]] || iOS, Android || || || [[Barry Sanders]] of the [[Detroit Lions]] (Xbox 360 and PS3) <br /> [[Adrian Peterson]] of the [[Minnesota Vikings]] (Xbox One and PS4)\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 15]]'' || 2014 || || || || || Xbox 360, PS3 || Xbox One, PS4 || || || || [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]] of the [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL Mobile|Madden NFL Overdrive]]'' || 2014 || || || || || || || iOS, Android || || || [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]] of the [[Seattle Seahawks]] (2014 season), [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] of the [[New York Giants]] (2015 season), [[Rob Gronkowski]] of the [[New England Patriots]]/[[Von Miller]] of the [[Denver Broncos]]/[[Antonio Brown]] of the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (2016 season), [[Tom Brady]] of the [[New England Patriots]] (2017 season), Antonio Brown of the Pittsburgh Steelers (2018 season)\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 16]]'' || 2015 || || || || || Xbox 360, PS3 || Xbox One, PS4 || || || || [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] of the [[New York Giants]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 17]]'' || 2016 || || || || || Xbox 360, PS3 || Xbox One, PS4 || || || || [[Rob Gronkowski]] of the [[New England Patriots]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 18]]'' || 2017 || || || || || || Xbox One, PS4 || || || || [[Tom Brady]] of the [[New England Patriots]]\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 19]]'' || 2018 || Windows || || || || || Xbox One, PS4, || || || || [[Antonio Brown]] of the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Terrell Owens]] of the [[Dallas Cowboys]] for the Hall of Fame Edition \n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL 20]]'' || 2019 || Windows || || || || || Xbox One, PS4, || || || || [[Patrick Mahomes]] of the Kansas City Chiefs\n|-\n|}\n\n===1980s: Creation===\n{{rquote|right|The real reason that I founded Electronic Arts was because I wanted to make computerized versions of games like Strat-O-Matic.|Trip Hawkins{{r|lemire20110210}}}}\n\n[[Trip Hawkins]] created a clone of the [[Strat-o-Matic]] paper and dice-based football simulation game as a teenager. The game was unsuccessful due to its complexity, and he hoped to one day delegate its rules to a computer. At [[Harvard College]], where Hawkins played football for the [[Harvard Crimson football|Crimson]], he wrote a football simulation for the [[PDP-11]] minicomputer which, he later said, predicted that the [[Miami Dolphins]] would defeat the [[Minnesota Vikings]] 23\u20136 (actually 24\u20137) in the [[1974 Super Bowl]].{{r|thefranchise}}<ref name=\"ferrell198805\">{{cite news |url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-05-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_096_1988_May#page/n15/mode/2up |title=These Are a Few of Their Favorite Games |work=Compute! |date=May 1988 |accessdate=10 November 2013 |author=Ferrell, Keith |pages=14}}</ref> After founding Electronic Arts in 1982{{r|thefranchise}}\u2014\"The real reason that I founded [it] was because I wanted to make computerized versions of games like Strat-O-Matic\", Hawkins later said<ref name=\"lemire20110210\">{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/joe_lemire/02/10/strat.o.matic/index.html |title=Strat-O-Matic more than a game for its founder and devotees |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2011-02-10 |accessdate=December 10, 2012 |author=Lemire, Joe}}</ref>{{r|suellentrop20100125}}\u2014the company began designing a microcomputer football game. Hawkins first approached his favorite player [[Joe Montana]] to endorse the proposed game but the quarterback already had an endorsement deal with [[Atari Inc.]], and his second choice, [[California Golden Bears football|Cal]] coach [[Joe Kapp]], demanded royalties.<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />\n\nIn 1984 Hawkins approached Madden. He and game producer [[Joe Ybarra]] arranged a follow-up meeting with the broadcaster during an [[Amtrak]] train trip over two days because of Madden's [[fear of flying]].<ref name=\"thefranchise\">{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=100805/madden | title=The Franchise | publisher=ESPN | date=2010-08-05 | accessdate=23 January 2015 | author=Hruby, Patrick}}</ref><ref name=\"pham20090417\">{{cite news |last=Pham |first=Alex |title=Popular Madden NFL game will continue |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2009-04-17 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/apr/17/entertainment/et-madden-games17 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN_History\">{{cite web |last=Fahs |first=Travis |title=IGN Presents the History of Madden |website=IGN |date=2008-08-06 |url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/896/896893p1.html |accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>{{r|bissell20120117}} The EA executives promised that the proposed game would be a sophisticated football simulation, and asked the retired Oakland Raiders coach for his endorsement and expertise. Madden knew nothing about computers beyond his [[telestrator]] but agreed; he had taught a class at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] called \"Football for Fans\", and envisioned the program as a tool for teaching and testing plays.<ref name=\"thefranchise\" /><ref name=\"markazi20090821\">{{cite news |last=Markazi |first=Arash |title=John Madden talks retirement, video game, plans for '09 season |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2009-08-21 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/arash_markazi/08/21/john-madden-talks-retirement/index.html |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> (Madden continues to see the game as an educational tool. When asked in 2012 to describe ''Madden NFL'', he called it \"a way for people to learn the game and participate in the game at a pretty sophisticated level\".{{r|bissell20120117}}) Hawkins and Ybarra during the train trip learned football plays and strategies from Madden from sunrise to midnight.<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />\n\nEA likely expected Madden to endorse the game without participating in its design. Early plans envisioned six or seven players per team because of technical limitations but Madden insisted on having 11 players,<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />{{r|bissell20120117}} stating \"I'm not putting my name on it if it's not real.\"<ref name=\"IGN_History\" /> Ybarra, who had played [[chess]], not football, in high school, became an expert on the subject through his work, but found that 11 players overwhelmed contemporary home computers. Most projects that are as delayed as ''Madden'' are canceled; Ybarra and developer Robin Antonick needed three years, more than twice the length of the average development process. The project became known within the company as \"Trip's Folly\", and Madden believed at times that EA had given up.<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />\n\nThe company hired [[Bethesda Softworks]] to finish the game, but this only got them partway to their goal. While EA used many of its designs, including contributions to their physics engine,<ref name=\"escapist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/issues/issue_83/471-Bethesda-The-Right-Direction|title=Bethesda: The Right Direction|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> within a year Bethesda stopped working on ''Madden'' and sued EA over EA's failure to publish new versions of Bethesda's ''Gridiron!'' football game. This added to the delay.<ref name=\"IGN_History\" /> After a final development push, ''[[John Madden Football (1988)|John Madden Football]]'' debuted in 1988 for the [[Apple II series]] of computers.  Hawkins and an exhausted Ybarra (\"All my memories are of pain\") were able to move on to other projects.<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />\n\nMadden provided EA the [[1980 Oakland Raiders season|1980 Raiders]] playbook, and EA hired ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' writer Frank Cooney, who had designed his own [[miniature figure (gaming)|figurine]] football game with numerical skill ratings. Although the company could not yet legally use NFL teams' or players' names, Cooney obtained real plays from NFL teams.{{r|thefranchise}} The back of the box called the game \"The First Real Football Simulation\" and quoted Madden: \"Hey, if there aren't 11 players, it isn't real football.\" Documentation included diagrams of dozens of offensive and defensive plays with Madden's commentary on coaching strategies and philosophy.<ref name=\"c64sets\">{{cite web |url=http://www.c64sets.com/set.html?id=33&show_all=1 |title=John Madden Football by Electronic Arts |work=Commodore 64 Boxed Sets |accessdate=November 22, 2012}}</ref> The game sold moderately well<ref name=\"thefranchise\" /> but given the sophisticated playbook its interface was complex, and Madden's insistence on 11 players caused the game to run slowly.<ref name=\"IGN_History\" />\n\nDuring this period, Madden turned down the opportunity to buy an \"unlimited\" number of options for EA stock in its [[initial public offering]], a decision he later called \"the dumbest thing I ever did in my life\".<ref name=\"thefranchise\" />{{r|bissell20120117}}\n\n===1990s===\nIn early 1990 EA hired [[Park Place Productions]] to develop ''Madden'' for the [[Sega Genesis]] [[video game console]]. Park Place had developed ''[[ABC Monday Night Football (video game)|ABC Monday Night Football]]'' with \"arcade-style, action-heavy\" game play, and its ''Madden'' also emphasized [[hyperreality]] compared to the computer version's focus on exact simulation.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>{{r|horowitz20071123}} Impressed with Park Place's work, EA chose it for the Genesis ''Madden'' instead of completing an in-house version by Antonick.<ref name=\"harris201503\">{{cite web | url=http://readonlymemory.vg/john-madden-hockey | title=John Madden Hockey | publisher=Read-Only Memory | date=March 2015 | accessdate=28 March 2015 | author=Harris, Blake J.}}</ref>\n\nEA [[reverse engineered]] the console to sell the game without paying the standard $8 to $10 license fee per cartridge to Sega, then proposed a compromise of $2 per cartridge and a $2 million cap on the fee. The console maker agreed, afraid that EA would sell its reverse-engineered knowledge to other companies; the agreement saved EA $35 million over the next three years. As its own Joe Montana-endorsed football game would miss the 1990 [[Christmas shopping season]], Sega asked EA to let it sell ''Madden'' with the Montana name. EA refused, but offered an inferior alternative that lacked ''Madden'''s 3D graphics and most of its 113 plays.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/>{{r|horowitz20071123}} ''[[Joe Montana Football]]'' sold well despite shipping after Christmas 1990, and remained popular after [[BlueSky Software]] took over development.<ref name=\"IGN_History\"/> ''[[John Madden Football (1990 video game)|John Madden Football]]'' for the Genesis, however, became both the first hugely successful ''Madden'' game\u2014selling 400,000 copies when the company expected 75,000{{r|harris201503}}\u2014and the first [[killer app]] for EA and Sega, helping the console gain market share against the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]].<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/><ref name=\"IGN_History\"/> From 1992 to 1994, ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]'' placed the game at #1 in their monthly Top 100 Mega Drive Games of All Time.\n\nIn 1990, EA producer [[Richard Hilleman]] brought in veteran sports game designer [[Scott Orr]], who had founded the mid-1980s [[Commodore 64]] game publisher GameStar, and had led the design of their best-selling sports games. The team of Orr and Hilleman designed and led the development of what is today still recognizable as the modern ''Madden''. Early versions of ''Madden'' were created by external development studios such as Bethesda, [[Visual Concepts]], and [[Stormfront Studios]]. ''John Madden Football '92'' also featured the ambulance which would run over any players in its path.\n\nAfter Visual Concepts failed to deliver ''Madden NFL '96'' for the new [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in 1995, EA hired Tiburon Entertainment for ''Madden NFL '97''<ref name=\"IGN_History\"/> and later acquired the company, centralizing development in-house.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/> It planned to release ''John Madden Football'' as its first sports-based [[arcade game]], but the game was cancelled due to unenthusiastic reactions from [[Game testing|play testers]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Off the Wall at AMOA|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=76 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=January 1995|page=34}}</ref> EA's refusal to release ''Madden'' and other sports titles for the [[Dreamcast]] in 1999 contributed to the console's lack of success and Sega's exit from the hardware market.<ref name=\"IGN_History\"/>\n\n====Franchise Mode====\n{{expand section|date=September 2012}}\nIn 1998 Electronic Arts added \"Franchise Mode\" to ''Madden'', giving players the ability to play multiple seasons, make off-season draft picks, and trade players.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://articles.cnn.com/1998-09-04/tech/9809_04_madden99.idg_1_madden-nfl-big-year-playstation?_s=PM:TECH |title=Madden NFL 99 the best PC football game bar none - CNN |publisher=Articles.cnn.com |date=1998-09-04 |accessdate=2012-09-24 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nWithin Franchise Mode, players take on the role of General Manager and manage all personnel matters, including contracts, free agency, draft picks, and hiring and firing coaches. The player also acts as a head coach-like character (although there is a head coach figure in-game), choosing which players to play, making substitutions, running practices, practicing gameplans, etc.\n\nPlayers may play with any of the NFL's 32 franchises, and can choose whether or not to have trade deadlines, salary caps, and if they want to start their Franchise with a 49-round fantasy draft of all active NFL players. Players can also upload created teams for use in the game.\n\nOnce in game, players run training camp (individual drills for improving players' attributes), play in preseason games and compete in a regular 16-game NFL season, including playoffs and the Super Bowl. The player has the option to play any game in the simulation, including those involving other teams if they so desire, or may simulate through the games as they choose. Most versions of ''Madden'' give a player 30 years with their franchise, sometimes with an opportunity to apply for the Hall of Fame at the end of the simulation.\n\n===2000s===\n====''Madden NFL 2000''====\n====''Madden NFL 2001''====\n''[[Madden NFL 2001]]'' featured a segment called \"Great Games\" where one would be put in a situation where they control one team and would have to win the game with a set amount of time. If the player wins, they unlock either a new team or a stadium. Overall, there were more than 60 teams and over 80 stadiums in ''Madden NFL 2001''. [[Tennessee Titans]] running back [[Eddie George]] is the cover athlete.\n\n====''Madden NFL 2002''====\n''[[Madden NFL 2002]]'' featured for the first time Create-A-Team where one would make a team and play with that team in either Play Now or Franchise mode. It also featured Create-A-League mode but it never caught on. Create-A-Team was not featured in ''Madden NFL 13'' and moving teams was first featured in ''Madden NFL 2004'' called \"Stadium\" in the Franchise mode of the game. ''Madden NFL 2002'' was the 2nd highest selling game in 2002. [[Minnesota Vikings]] quarterback [[Daunte Culpepper]] is the cover athlete.\n\n====''Madden NFL 2003''====\nThere are multiple modes of game play, from a quick head-to-head game to running a team for a whole season or even multiple seasons. Online play, which was a new feature for ''[[Madden NFL 2003]]'' (in this version there are also mini-camp challenges) was only available for users of the [[PlayStation 2]] console, [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] console, or a [[Microsoft Windows]] PC until early [[2004 in video gaming|2004]]. [[St. Louis Rams]] running back [[Marshall Faulk]] is the cover athlete.<!-- At [[E3 (Electronic Entertainment Expo)|E3 2004]], Microsoft and EA Sports -->\n\n====''Madden NFL 2004''====\nAlso, starting with ''[[Madden NFL 2004]]'', EA Sports created the new ''Playmaker'' tool, using the right analog joystick found on each of the adjustments previously unavailable in prior installments of the franchise.<ref>{{cite web | last = Navarro | first = Alex | title = Madden NFL 2004 Impressions | website = [[GameSpot]] | date = 2003-07-09 | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/sports/madden2004/news.html?sid=6071304 | accessdate = 2009-04-01 }}</ref> One such adjustment includes the ability to switch which direction a running play was going without changing the formation. Prior to the Playmaker tool, the Player could only call one of four available \"hot routes.\" With Playmaker and the use of the right thumb stick, the player is given 4 additional Hot Route options. When the quarterback has the ball the Playmaker Tool can be used to make receivers alter their routes mid-play. When running the ball on offense, the runner can control the direction in which the blocker is going. Defensive alignment adjustments, however, were not available leading to obvious imbalance in favor of the Offensive player. [[Atlanta Falcons]] quarterback [[Michael Vick]] is the cover athlete.\n\n====''Madden NFL 2005''====\nIn ''[[Madden NFL 2005]]'', EA Sports ran a campaign with the Theme \"Fear the D\" emphasising their improvements on the \"other side of the ball.\" In an attempt to re-balance the players experience, EA gave a Playmaker Tool to the defense. Similar to the offensive Playmaker Tool, the defensive Playmaker allows the player to make pre-snap defensive adjustments. EA Sports further utilized the right analog joystick on defense by creating the \"Hit Stick\", an option on defense that allows the controlled player to make big hits, with a simple flick, that increases the chances the ball carrier will fumble. Also introduced for the first time is the \"Formation Shift.\" This new feature allowed players to shift their formation in the pre-snap audible menu without actually changing the play. For example, if you call a run play up the middle out of a goal line formation, you could then call a formation shift and make your players spread out into a four wide receiver formation while still in the same running play. The problem with this new function was that EA also added a fatigue penalty for the defense causing defensive players to get more tired each time there was a formation shift. This led to players on offense calling multiple formation shifts each play making the defensive players too exhausted to keep up and force them to substitute out of the game until they are fully rested. This led to more imbalance that could only be fixed by turning off fatigue. [[Baltimore Ravens]] linebacker [[Ray Lewis]] is the cover athlete.\n\n''2005'' also added \"EA Sports Radio\", a fictional show that plays during the menu screen of Franchise mode to provide a greater sense of a storyline during gameplay. It features [[Tony Bruno]] as the host, who often interviews players and coaches about how the season is going and also has quiz questions in which fake listeners call in to make attempts at answering football-related questions. It included mock interviews of famous NFL players and coaches throughout the in-game season. Some fans have criticized [[EA Sports]] for not including new features to the 'programming' as the radio became stale after only two seasons in franchise mode, but the feature drew acclaim for adding content to the Franchise menu. Also added was the Newspaper where the player could look at National News from licensed USA Today and Licensed Local papers for almost each of the 32 NFL teams. Lastly, 2005 also saw the introduction of multiple progressions during franchise mode. Previously NFL players in Madden would only progress or regress at the end of each season. Now at the end of Week 5, 11, and 17 the game would use a program to \"progress\" players based on their performance in addition to end of season progression.\n\n====''Madden NFL 06''====\nIn ''[[Madden NFL 06]]'', the \"Truck Stick\" was introduced. This feature allows the offensive player to lower his shoulder and break a tackle, or back juke to avoid one. Another new feature is the ''[[Be-a-pro mode|Superstar Mode]]'', which allows the player to take control of a rookie, and progress through his career.<ref>{{cite web | last = Ekberg | first = Brian | title = Madden NFL 06 Superstar Mode Preview | website = GameSpot | date = 2005-07-01 | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/sports/maddennfl2006/news.html?sid=6128568 | accessdate = 2009-04-01 }}</ref> This includes an IQ test, interviews, workouts, the NFL Draft, hiring an agent, and other aspects of a superstar's life. [[Philadelphia Eagles]] quarterback [[Donovan McNabb]] is the cover athlete.\n\nEA also introduced the ''QB Vision'' feature in the 2006 installment. With this feature, a cone of spotlight emits from the quarterback during passing plays, simulating his field of vision. To make an accurate pass, the quarterback must have his intended receiver in his field of vision. Passing to a receiver not in the cone reduces pass accuracy significantly. The size of the quarterback's vision cone is directly correlated to his Awareness and Passer Accuracy rating; [[Brett Favre]] and [[Peyton Manning]] see nearly the entire field at once, whereas an inexperienced quarterback such as [[J. P. Losman]] or [[Kyle Boller]] sees only a sliver of the field.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/> This feature also allows for bigger plays and more interceptions.\n\nAlso, EA sports added the ''Smart Route''. This means that when pressing a hot route to the corresponding receiver, you put the analog stick down and the receiver will run to the first down, and you can throw him the ball.\n\nWhile current gen Madden remained the same with the exception of a \"Smart Route\" and \"QB Vision\", this was also the first year Madden was released on the next-gen Xbox 360. It was completely stripped down, almost every change made in the previous gen was wiped away.\n\n====''EA Sports Madden NFL Football''====\nThis is an arcade game developed by [[Global VR]], and released in 2005. The game comes in standard and deluxe cabinets. It can be played with up to four players, and includes five game modes: Exhibition, Training, Tournament, Competition, and Career. It features rosters from the 2004-2005 season.<ref>{{cite web | title = EA Sports Madden NFL Football flyer | url = https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/flyers_video/globalvr/332000302.jpg | accessdate = 2019-09-01 }}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 07''====\nIn ''[[Madden NFL 07]]'', EA introduced ''Lead Blocker Controls'' which allow users to control blockers during running plays. In addition, EA redefined the Truck Stick into the ''Highlight Stick''. With the Highlight Stick, users can have their running backs perform different running moves and combos, instead of just bowling over defenders. Truck Stick features still exist for bigger backs, but not for smaller backs who would never realistically use them anyway. Instead, more agile backs perform acrobatic ducks and dodges to avoid tackles.<ref>{{cite web | last = Navarro | first = Alex | title = Madden NFL 07 Review | website = GameSpot | date = 2006-08-22 | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/sports/madden07/review.html | accessdate = 2009-04-01 }}</ref> [[Seattle Seahawks]] running back [[Shaun Alexander]] is the cover athlete.\n\n====''EA Sports Madden NFL Football: Season 2''====\nThis game is the sequel to EA Sports Madden NFL Football. Like the original, it was also developed by [[Global VR]]. It was released in 2006 only in arcades. This version adds QB Vision, the Hit Stick, and the Truck Stick. The rosters are also updated for the 2006-2007 season.<ref>{{cite web | title = EA Sports Madden NFL Football: Season 2 flyer | url = https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/flyers_video/globalvr/332002801.jpg | accessdate = 2019-09-01 }}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 08''====\nIn ''[[Madden NFL 08]]'', the ''Weapons'' feature was added, allowing superstar players to be noticed. [[Randy Moss]], for example, is a Go-To-Guy, allowing him to make amazing one-handed grabs. [[Peyton Manning]] is a Franchise QB. It also includes new skill drills, Hit Stick 2.0, and Ring of a Champion features. [[Tennessee Titans]] quarterback [[Vince Young]] is on the cover.\nMadden NFL 08 was also the last [[GameCube]] game ever released. The 2008 edition would be the last to appear on PC until Madden 19 in 2018.\n\n====''Madden NFL 09''====\n''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' was released on August 12, 2008. Citing business concerns, EA chose not to release it on the PC platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20080403-another-blow-for-pc-gaming-ea-drops-pc-version-of-madden-09.html|title=Another blow for PC gaming: EA drops PC version of Madden '09|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> The game features quarterback [[Brett Favre]] on the front cover, initially in a [[Green Bay Packers]] uniform, but also with a downloadable cover featuring Favre in a [[New York Jets]] uniform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/videogames/news/story?id=3366051|title=Madden NFL 09 cover to feature NFL great Brett Favre|date=25 April 2008|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> Favre had retired before the start of the season as a member of the Packers, but came out of retirement late in the summer and was traded to the Jets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kotaku.com/first-look-at-new-brett-favre-madden-jets-cover-5035824|work=Kotaku|title=First Look At New Brett Favre Madden Jets Cover|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> ''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' was the first of the series to offer online, league game play, allowing up to 32 players to compete in an online, simulated NFL season. EA Sports Senior Producer Phil Frazier, up to 32 players were able to participate in competitive games, the NFL Draft and conduct trades between their teams. The game was also the first of the series to incorporate a Madden IQ. The Madden IQ is used to automatically gauge your skills through a series of mini-games consisting of run offense, pass offense, run defense, and pass defense. At the end of each of the drills, the player receives a score ranging from rookie to all-Madden. The final Madden IQ is a mixture of those scores which is used to control the game's difficulty.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/sports/maddennfl09/news.html?sid=6189938&om_act=convert&om_clk=newsfeatures&tag=newsfeatures;title;1:|title=Madden NFL 09|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/sports/maddennfl09/news.html?sid=6191473&mode=previews:|title=Madden NFL 09|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 10''====\n''[[Madden NFL 10]]'' was released on August 14, 2009. It features [[Arizona Cardinals]] wide receiver [[Larry Fitzgerald]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] strong safety [[Troy Polamalu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.gamespot.com/sports/blogs/sports-blog/909097139/26870251/madden-nfl-10-ea-answers-your-questions.html|title=GameSpot: EA Answers Your Questions|accessdate=15 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510003344/http://uk.gamespot.com/sports/blogs/sports-blog/909097139/26870251/madden-nfl-10-ea-answers-your-questions.html|archivedate=10 May 2009}}</ref> Compared to previous iterations, Madden NFL 10 has been extremely transparent with its development efforts, maintaining a weekly blog updates as well as a constant presence on various message boards. A new design team has also taken over the game, including members from NFL Head Coach 09. The direction of Madden NFL 10 has been shifted to much more of a realistic and simulation focus, with info already released including Procedural Awareness (a robust head tracking system), a new philosophy on player ratings, and big improvements to realism in QB play, WR/DB play, and other areas across the game. Madden 10 has several new features including the PRO-TAK animation technology, which allows up to nine man gang tackles and fumble pile-ups to help players 'fight for every yard', in this year's tagline. Madden 10 also features an in-game weekly recap show called The Extra Point. Madden 10 offers a series of multiple play packages. This allows for more options to score. This version features a completely overhauled rating system for players, featuring new categories such as throw on the run and specific ratings for short, medium, and deep passes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/firstcuts/entry/view/28609/houshmandzadeh_mad_about_madden_rating|title=Sporting News - NFL - NCAA - NBA - MLB - NASCAR - UFC - WWE|website=Sporting News|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731132328/http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/firstcuts/entry/view/28609/houshmandzadeh_mad_about_madden_rating|archivedate=2009-07-31}}</ref> The game's soundtrack features rap, alternative rock, rap metal and hard rock bands such as [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Pantera]], [[System of a Down]], and [[Kid Rock]].\n\n===2010s===\n====''Madden NFL 11''====\n''[[Madden NFL 11]]'' was released on July 27, 2010 (moved up from its original release date of August 10, 2010 for promotional reasons<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=ap-games-madden|title=NFL on Yahoo! Sports - News, Scores, Standings, Rumors, Fantasy Games|website=Yahoo Sports}}</ref>), and features [[New Orleans Saints]] quarterback [[Drew Brees]] on the cover. It features several new additions to the franchise, such as Online Team Play,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/new-madden-11-video-talks-online-team-play-with-designers/|title=New Madden 11 Video Talks Online Team Play with Designers - GoMadden<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> Online Scouting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/madden-11-to-introduce-enhanced-online-scouting/|title=Madden 11 to Introduce Enhanced Online Scouting - GoMadden<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> and online attribute boosts for co-op play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/madden-11-boosts-to-be-purchasable/|title=Madden 11 Boosts to be Purchasable - GoMadden<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> Along with these new game additions is a new rating (sponsored by Old Spice) known as Swagger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/madden-11-has-lots-of-swagger-literally/ |title=Madden 11 Has Lots of Swagger\u2026 Literally - GoMadden |accessdate=15 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702151847/http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/madden-11-has-lots-of-swagger-literally |archivedate=2 July 2010 }}</ref> Although early speculation was that this new rating would be reflective of \"confidence\" or \"composure,\" it was quickly confirmed to be directly tied to a player's personality for celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gomadden.com/news/footballgame/madden-11-swagger-is-pure-personality/|title=Madden 11 Swagger is Pure Personality - GoMadden<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 12''====\n''[[Madden NFL 12]]'' was released on August 25, 2011. The release was delayed by two weeks due to the [[2011 NFL lockout|NFL lockout]],<ref>{{cite news |title='Madden NFL 12' release delayed three weeks |url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/story/permalink/23440 |work=[[Pro Football Weekly]] |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=2012-03-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509184344/http://www.profootballweekly.com/story/permalink/23440 |archivedate=May 9, 2011 }}</ref> and features [[Cleveland Browns]] [[running back]] [[Peyton Hillis]] on the cover. However, there is a limited edition in which the cover features [[St. Louis Rams]] running back [[Marshall Faulk]].\n\n====''Madden NFL 13''====\n''[[Madden NFL 13]]'' was released on August 28, 2012, and features [[Detroit Lions]] [[wide receiver]] [[Calvin Johnson]] as the cover athlete. ''Madden NFL 13'' is the first ''Madden'' game to be released on the [[PlayStation Vita]], and is also the first game in the series to have [[Kinect]] support as well as a new physics engine promoting real in game physics.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stein |first=Scott |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-57499940-1/madden-13-on-vita-and-kinect-new-technology-in-the-huddle/ |title=Madden 13 on Vita and Kinect: New technology in the huddle &#124; Crave - CNET |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=2012-08-24 |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\n''Madden NFL 13'' included a complete revamp to online franchise mode which became known as Connected Careers Mode (CCM). Some of the new CCM features included player contracts, the ability to trade draft picks, a salary cap, and up to 30 seasons worth of gameplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-athlete.net/blog/3/entry-208-madden-13-online-franchise-replaced-by-connected-careers-mode/#.U-QltvldVdU |title= Madden 13: Online Franchise Replaced by Connected Careers Mode  |publisher=e-Athlete.net |date=2012-06-04 |accessdate=2014-08-07}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 25''====\n{{Main|Madden NFL 25}}\nIn early 2013, EA Sports announced that the next installment of the Madden series would be released on August 27, 2013. As this installment is the 25th anniversary of the series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news/article/madden-25-coming-soon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201183400/http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news/article/madden-25-coming-soon|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 1, 2013|title=Madden 25 Coming Soon|publisher=easports.com|date=January 29, 2013|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> the game is called ''Madden NFL 25'', instead of ''Madden NFL 14'' with the year like the previous versions.<ref name=\"Madden 25 confirmed\">{{cite web|last=Goldfarb|first=Andrew|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/01/ea-confirms-madden-nfl-25?abthid=510bf9c97463d5c65500007d|title=EA confirms Madden NFL 25|website=[[IGN]]|date=February 1, 2013|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> The cover vote consisted of two brackets containing past players (\"Old School\") and active players (\"New School\").<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayer|first=Larry|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/news/article-1/Forte-in-running-for-Madden-cover/e0315b79-1895-4f1a-8673-5d3e5532dabe|title=Forte in running for Madden cover|publisher=[[Chicago Bears]]|date=March 12, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"Old School\" player and [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]r [[Barry Sanders]] was chosen as the cover athlete for ''Madden NFL 25'' on the April 24, 2013, episode of [[ESPN]]'s ''[[SportsNation (TV series)|SportsNation]]''. The \"New School\" finalist was [[Adrian Peterson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sportsnation/story/_/id/9208257/barry-sanders-wins-madden-25-cover-vote-adrian-peterson-minnesota-vikings|title=Barry Sanders wins Madden vote|work=[[ESPN]]|date=April 24, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 15''====\n{{Main|Madden NFL 15}}\nOn March 13, 2014 [[EA Sports]] posted on its website that user would be able to design and submit uniforms for Connected Careers by March 17, 2014 for \"the next Madden NFL.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = DESIGN LOGOS AND UNIFORMS FOR THE NEXT MADDEN NFL | publisher = EA Sports | date = 2014-03-13 | url = http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news-updates-gameplay/article/uniform-design-contest | accessdate = 2014-04-12 }}</ref> On April 28, 2014, EA announced the release of Madden 15 pre-ordering in a release video with NFL linebacker and 2013 Defensive Player of the Year [[Luke Kuechly]]. The game was released August 26 in North America and on August 29 in the EU for Xbox One, PlayStation 4, Xbox 360 and the PlayStation 3. The game featured \"dramatic all-new camera angles, as well as dynamic pre-game and halftime features.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Madden NFL 15 Available on August 26 | publisher = EA Sports | date = 2014-04-29 | url = http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news-updates-gameplay/article/madden-15-release-date | accessdate = 2014-04-30 }}</ref> During the Detroit Lions 10th pick of the [[2014 NFL Draft]], Barry Sanders announced fans again would be able to vote for the cover athlete.<ref>{{cite web | title = Madden NFL 15 Cover Vote Now Underway | publisher = EA Sports | date = 2014-05-09 | url = http://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news-updates-gameplay/article/madden-15-cover-vote | accessdate = 2014-05-09 }}</ref> On June 6, [[Seattle Seahawks]] [[cornerback]] [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]] was announced as the cover athlete.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Farrar|first1=Doug|title=Seahawks CB Richard Sherman wins Madden NFL 15 cover vote|url=http://nfl.si.com/2014/06/06/richard-sherman-madden-15-cover-seahawks/?eref=sihp|magazine=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=June 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140607061007/http://nfl.si.com/2014/06/06/richard-sherman-madden-15-cover-seahawks/?eref=sihp|archivedate=June 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 16''====\n{{Main|Madden NFL 16}}\nEA decided not to have players vote for the cover athlete through a traditional bracket, but rather through collectible cards in ''[[Madden NFL Mobile]]'', or through Ultimate Team on the console devices. On May 4, 2015, the four finalists were announced for the 2016 game cover: [[New England Patriots]] tight end [[Rob Gronkowski]], [[Arizona Cardinals]] cornerback [[Patrick Peterson]], [[New York Giants]] wide receiver [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] wide receiver [[Antonio Brown]]. On May 13, Beckham Jr. beat out Gronkowski in a fan vote for the cover of ''Madden 16''. It was released on August 25, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Odell Beckham makes cover of Madden 2016|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000492622/article/odell-beckham-makes-cover-of-madden-2016|website=NFL.com|accessdate=May 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 17''====\n{{main|Madden NFL 17}}\n''[[Madden NFL 17]]'' was released on August 23, 2016. The features in the game include an upgrade of the Ground Game, a redesigned and better Franchise Mode, \"Madden 365\", new Ball Carrier UI Prompts, the new Path Assist and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/madden-nfl/news/2016/madden-nfl-17-features-overview|title=Madden NFL 17 Features Overview|website=www.easports.com|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref> [[New England Patriots]] tight end [[Rob Gronkowski]] serves as the cover athlete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15520923/new-england-patriots-te-rob-gronkowski-cover-madden-nfl-17|title=Game on: Gronk gets cover of 'Madden NFL '17'|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 18''====\n{{main|Madden NFL 18}}\n''[[Madden NFL 18]]'' was released on August 25, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/madden-nfl|title=Madden NFL 18 - Football Video Game - EA SPORTS Official Site|website=www.easports.com}}</ref> The game is the first in the series to be developed in the [[Frostbite (game engine)|Frostbite Engine]], and incorporates a story mode titled Longshot Mode, akin to ''The Journey'' in [[FIFA 17]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/madden-nfl-18-release-date-new-features-game-play-mode-cover-tom-brady/g3gl89sady92zjry45hyp1fq|title='Madden NFL 18' to introduce story mode, feature new play styles|date=12 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref> It was announced that [[New England Patriots]] quarterback [[Tom Brady]] would be on the cover, marking the second consecutive year where a Patriot will be on the cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/19363661/new-england-patriots-qb-tom-brady-cover-madden-nfl-18|title=GOAT edition: Brady on 'Madden NFL 18' cover|publisher=}}</ref> Furthermore, an enhanced '''G.O.A.T''' edition was also announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/games/2017/05/what-is-madden-18-goat-edition-features-cover-release-date-meaning-comes-with-price-when/|title=\u2018Madden 18\u2019 GOAT Edition: Release Date, Features & Price|first=Jonathan|last=Adams|date=13 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL 19''====\n{{main|Madden NFL 19}}\n''[[Madden NFL 19]]'' was announced with [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] wide receiver [[Antonio Brown]] as the cover athlete.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24129734/steelers-wr-antonio-brown-madden-19-cover|title=Game on: Antonio Brown on Madden 19 cover|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref> It was released on August 10, 2018. The game was released to the PC in addition to the console versions, the first one to do so since ''Madden NFL 08'' in 2007.\n\n====''Madden NFL 20''====\n{{main|Madden NFL 20}}\n''[[Madden NFL 20]]'' was announced with [[Kansas City Chiefs]] quarterback [[Patrick Mahomes]] as the cover athlete.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/kansas-city-chiefs-quarterback-patrick-mahomes-covers-madden-20/|title=Patrick Mahomes becomes fifth black QB on \u2018Madden 20\u2019 cover|work=The Undefeated|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> It was released on August 2, 2019.\n\n===License history and spinoffs===\n====Licensing====\nUntil 1993, the Madden series did not have official licenses from the [[National Football League]] (NFL) or [[National Football League Players Association]] (NFLPA). ''[[Madden NFL '94]]'' was the first game in the series to include real NFL teams, and ''[[Madden NFL '95]]'' added an NFLPA license for real players through the [[National Football League Players Incorporated]] (NFLPI).<ref>{{cite web|title=Then And Now: Madden Football Turns Twenty|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/6195748/index.html|website=GameSpot.com|date=August 11, 2008|access-date=April 3, 2009}}</ref> The licenses restrict EA from including certain content in current ''Madden'' games, such as the humorous ambulance that picks up injured players in 1991's ''[[John Madden Football II]]''.{{r|thefranchise}} The NFL Coaches Association sold the rights to have NFL coaches' names appear in the ''Madden NFL'' games; ''[[Madden NFL 2001]]'' was the first game in the series to feature this license.<ref>{{cite web | last = Ajami | first = Amer | title = Madden NFL 2001 First Impressions | website = GameSpot | date = 2000-05-13 | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/sports/maddennfl2001/news.html?sid=2569203 | accessdate = 2009-04-03 }}</ref> Neither [[New England Patriots]] coach [[Bill Belichick]] nor [[Bill Parcells]] appeared in the game as they are not members of the NFL Coaches Association. Likewise, non-NFLPA players (such as [[Thurman Thomas]] during his playing career) do not appear in the game, instead being replaced with generic placeholders.\n\n=====Exclusivity=====\nIn 2004, EA signed an exclusive licensing rights agreement through 2009 with the NFL and the NFLPA to give the company the exclusive rights to use the NFL's teams, stadia, and players in a video game.<ref>{{cite web|title=EA and NFL ink exclusive licensing agreement|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/2004/12/13/news_6114977.html|website=GameSpot.com|date=December 13, 2004|access-date=June 14, 2007}}</ref> This exclusive license prevents other rival video game developers from producing official NFL video games. The deal, reportedly worth $300 million and later extended to 2013,<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/> has been widely criticized. Some competitors, such as the ''[[Blitz: The League]]'' series, have elected to continue, seeking to distinguish themselves through innovative gameplay while others, such as the ''[[NFL 2K (series)|NFL 2K]]'' series, have ceased production. In 2007, 2K Sports released ''[[All Pro Football 2K8]]'', which used former NFL stars.\n\n====''Head Coach'' series====\n{{main|NFL Head Coach}}\n\nIn August 2006, [[EA Sports]] debuted ''[[NFL Head Coach]]'', which utilized the ''Madden'' engine to create a football management simulation. The game was criticized as buggy and unrealistic. EA Tiburon rebuilt the game from the ground up, addressing flaws and creating a proprietary engine, over the course of three years. ''[[NFL Head Coach 09]]'' was released on August 12, 2008 bundled with the special edition of ''Madden NFL 09'' and as a standalone game on September 2, 2008.\n\n====''Madden NFL Social''====\n''Madden NFL Social'' was an early version of ''[[Madden NFL Mobile]]'' for [[Facebook]] and [[iOS]] that was released November 1, 2012 and shut down September 2, 2013.\n\n====''Madden Arcade''====\nReleased on November 24, 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/105/1050591p1.html|title=Madden NFL Arcade Review|first=By Jeff|last=Haynes|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> the game is 5-on-5 and takes the best 10 players from each of the 32 NFL teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maddennfl.easports.com/arcade.action|title=Madden NFL 17 - EA SPORTS - Official Site|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208224527/http://maddennfl.easports.com/arcade.action|archive-date=8 February 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====''Madden NFL Mobile ''====\n''[[Madden NFL Mobile]]'' was released on August 26, 2014 and is only the third Madden game on mobile devices. The game is very similar to the Madden Ultimate Team (MUT) game mode, and the game is currently on its 6th season.\n\n====''Madden NFL Football''====\n''[[Madden NFL Football]]'' was released as a launch title for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] on March 27, 2011.<ref>[http://www.gamespot.com/3ds/sports/maddennfl/news.html?sid=6286560&mode=previews Madden NFL Football 3DS Hands-On - GameSpot.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122010234/http://www.gamespot.com/3ds/sports/maddennfl/news.html?sid=6286560&mode=previews |date=2011-01-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\nIn 1996, ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed the Genesis installments of the series collectively as number 30 on their \"Top 100 Games of All Time\", calling them \"One of the best two-player games of all time, the game that reinvented EA, and (along with ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'') the game that launched [[Sega]]'s 16-bit assault on [[Nintendo]].\"<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|pages=59}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-1990s, the series came under increasing criticism for its exploitable AI in single-player mode, as certain plays would consistently trounce AI-controlled teams,<ref>{{cite magazine |author1=Kraig Kujawa |author2=Sushi-X|title=The War on AI |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=99 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=October 1997|page=76}}</ref> and came to be regarded as primarily a multiplayer experience.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Madden '97 |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=24|publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=December 1996|page=256}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents===\n[[Jacksonville Landing shooting|On August 26, 2018]], a [[mass shooting]] occurred at an eSports tournament in [[Jacksonville, Florida]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/08/26/mass-shooting-reported-at-jacksonville-landing-police-say.html |title=Gunman at Jacksonville Landing gaming event kills 2 before killing himself, investigators say |first=Katherine |last=Lam |first2=Travis |last2=Fedschun |first3=Nicole |last3=Darrah |access-date=August 26, 2018 |work=[[Fox News]] |date=August 26, 2018 |publisher=[[FOX]]}}</ref> that was a qualification event for the ''Madden NFL'' Championship Series, playing ''[[Madden NFL 19]]''. The incident was [[live-streamed]] on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], and shots can be heard in the streaming coverage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gunman kills 2, fatally shoots himself at video game tournament in Jacksonville, Fl. |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4410419/mass-shooting-jacksonville-video-game-event/ |date=August 26, 2018 |access-date=27 August 2018 |newspaper=[[Global News]] |first=Rahul |last=Kalvapalle |publisher=[[Corus Entertainment Inc.]]}}</ref> 3 people, including the suspect was killed and at least 11 people were injured. One victim was not hurt by gunfire. <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/26/us/jacksonville-madden-shooting/index.html |title=Two killed in shooting at Jacksonville video game tournament |first=Eric |last=Levenson |first2=AnneClaire |last2=Stapleton |first3=Darran |last3=Simon |date=26 August 2018 |work=[[CNN World]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.]] |agency=[[Cable News Network]] |access-date=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Madden Curse==\nPrior to 1998, every annual installment of the ''Madden NFL'' series primarily featured Madden on its cover.<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/><ref name='GBFOX'>{{cite news| title = Favre a Victim of the 'Madden Curse?' |date=2008-07-17 |publisher=[[WLUK-TV]] |url=http://www.myfoxnewisconsin.com/myfox/pages/Home/Detail?contentId=7007597&version=7&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=VSTY&pageId=1.1.1 |work=myfoxnewisconsin.com |accessdate=2008-07-24}}</ref> In 1998, [[Electronic Arts]] selected [[Garrison Hearst]] to appear on the PAL version's cover, and has since featured one of the league's top players on every annual installment<ref name=\"snoops\">{{cite web |first=Barbara | last=Mikkelson |author2=David P. Mikkelson |title=The Madden Curse|website=Snopes.com |url=http://www.snopes.com/sports/football/maddencurse.asp |date=2007-10-21 |accessdate=2008-01-03}}</ref> despite Madden's opposition.{{r|thefranchise}} While appearing on the cover has become an honor akin to [[List of athletes on Wheaties boxes|appearing on the Wheaties box]],<ref name=\"thefranchise\"/> much like the [[Sports Illustrated Cover Jinx|''Sports Illustrated'' Cover Jinx]], certain players who appeared on ''Madden'' video game box art have experienced a decline in performance or an injury. This apparent run of misfortune for ''Madden'' cover athletes has been dubbed the \"Madden Curse.\"<ref name=SN>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com/nfl/gallery/madden-nfl-curse-cover-athlete-ranked-least-most-seasons-2018-051217|author=Cameron DaSilva|title=Every Madden NFL cover athlete, from least to most cursed|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|accessdate=2018-04-27}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked about the Madden Curse, EA Sports' [[Christopher Erb|Chris Erb]] said, \"I don't know that we believe in the curse. The players don't believe in the curse.\"<ref name='JS'>{{cite news |first=Greg |last=Pearson |title=Chapter, verse on the curse |date=2007-07-09 |url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=629939 |work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |accessdate=2008-07-17 }}</ref> [[Running back]] [[Shaun Alexander]], who was featured on the cover of ''[[Madden NFL 07]]'', commented, \"Do you want to be hurt and on the cover, or just hurt?\" ''[[Madden NFL 08]]'' cover athlete [[Vince Young]] expressed skepticism,<ref>{{cite news |first=Kyle |last=Orland |title=Vince Young talks Madden curse on Jimmy Kimmel Live |date=2007-04-18 |publisher=Joystiq |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/04/18/vince-young-talks-madden-curse-on-jimmy-kimmel-live/ |accessdate=2008-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Erik |last=Malinowski |title=Tomlinson Turned down 'Madden 08' Cover |date=2007-04-18 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=http://blog.wired.com/games/2007/04/tomlinson_turne.html |accessdate=2008-07-17}}</ref> while ''[[Madden NFL 12]]'' cover athlete [[Peyton Hillis]] attributed his subpar season that year to the curse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/7405565/after-tough-season-cleveland-browns-peyton-hillis-believer-madden-video-game-curse/ |title=After tough season, Cleveland Browns' Peyton Hillis a believer in Madden video game curse |publisher=ESPN |date=2011-12-30 |accessdate=2012-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe perception that the curse is real has resulted in some fans lobbying for their favorite players not to be on the cover, such as fans of [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] who were strongly opposed to EA Sports' initial decision to feature him on the cover of ''[[Madden NFL 08]]'', so much that a fan created ''SaveLTfromMadden.com'' to voice their disdain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/blogs/sidebar/909182374/25566571/chargers-fans-plead-to-keep-lt-off-madden-cover.html|title=Chargers fans plead to keep LT off Madden cover|date=2007-04-16|publisher=GameStop|accessdate=2008-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/gaming/madden/fans-want-madden-coverboy-dropped-fear-the-curse-252780.php |title=Fans Want Madden Coverboy Dropped, Fear The Curse |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=2007-04-16 |website=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=2008-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220164344/http://kotaku.com/gaming/madden/fans-want-madden-coverboy-dropped-fear-the-curse-252780.php |archivedate=2008-12-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"toml\">{{cite news |first=Darren |last=Rovell |title=Tomlinson Turns Down Madden, Rutgers Coach Cashes In, No Texting & Another MJ |date=2008-07-18 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/18175081/ |publisher=CNBC |accessdate=2008-07-17}}</ref> Tomlinson eventually declined the offer, but stated it was solely due to contract negotiations.<ref name=\"toml\"/> Starting with ''Madden NFL 11'' EA has allowed fans to choose their favorite player for the cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=5125018|title=Fans pick Brees for cover of Madden 11 game|date=22 April 2010|publisher=|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> However, EA believes that many fans vote against their favorite player to avoid the purported \"curse\".{{r|bissell20120117}} It has become so prominent that bookmakers create odds on how likely an injury will occur to the player appearing on the cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbettingonline.ag/articles/sportsbettingonline-asks-sports-bettors-if-madden-curse-will-topple-calvin-megatronjohnson.php |title=Would Madden Curse Topple Calvin \"Megatron\"Johnson? |publisher=Sportsbettingonline.ag |date=2012-04-26 |accessdate=2012-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe injuries that ''Madden'' cover athletes experience can be attributed to the physical nature of football.<ref name=JS /> Also to earn the honor of being put on the game cover, a player is usually coming off of a strong year and [[Regression to the mean|some regression the following year is likely]]. Attributing some cause, such as a curse, to this randomness is a [[regression fallacy]] and a [[spurious correlation]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nIn December 2010, EA announced plans on developing a movie based on the Curse, which would be a comedy, and not based on fate-based horror movies like ''[[Final Destination]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/madden-curse-electronic-arts/65888/?_r=true |title=Electronic Arts Developing MADDEN CURSE Movie |publisher=Collider.com |accessdate=2012-08-09}}</ref> However, EA Entertainment executive Pat O'Brien stated in October 2014 that EA is not working on a Madden Curse movie.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Koopa|first1=Ludwig|title=Madden Curse Movie: CANCELED!?|url=http://koopatv.org/2014/12/madden-curse-movie-canceled.html|website=KoopaTV|publisher=KoopaTV|accessdate=17 July 2015|ref=KoopaTV|date=12 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721070637/http://www.koopatv.org/2014/12/madden-curse-movie-canceled.html|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Patrick Mahomes]] of the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] won the Super Bowl and Super Bowl MVP, the curse was considered \"broken\", despite the fact that Mahomes did suffer a knee injury earlier in the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/2/21119772/patrick-mahomes-madden-cover-curse-super-bowl-mvp|title=Patrick Mahomes officially broke the Madden cover curse|publisher=Polygon \\accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/super-bowl-2020-patrick-mahomes-breaks-madden-curse-with-win-over-49ers-ea-sports-reacts-what-curse</ref>\n\n==Madden Bowl==\nThe Madden Bowl is a single elimination tournament held on the most current edition of ''Madden NFL''. It has been held since [[Super Bowl XXIX|1995]] during Super Bowl weekend in the host city and, in the past, participation included NFL players and celebrities. The Madden Bowl's participation has changed over the years from being an event held with athletes, musicians, and celebrities, to become an event where only NFL players who are invited to participate get a chance to play. Participants in the Madden Bowl are free to choose whichever team they like. Winners receive a Madden Bowl trophy and recognition in the upcoming ''Madden'' video game.\n\nThe 2006 Madden Bowl, held during the weekend of [[Super Bowl XL]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], was televised on [[ESPN]] and premiered in April 2006. Concurrently, ESPN also hosted a separate series of competitions called ''[[Madden Nation]]'', which was a [[reality television]] show that chronicled a cross-country trip to crown the best Madden player in the United States and aired from 2005 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operationsports.com/news/269002/espn2s-madden-nation-to-begin-fourth-season/ |title=ESPN2's Madden Nation to Begin Fourth Season |publisher=Operation Sports |author=Steve_OS |date=15 September 2008 |accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2011 to 2012, the Madden Bowl competition utilizes the new Online Team Play feature included in ''[[Madden NFL 11]]''. Rather than competing as individuals, players form groups of three to square-off for the trophy. After this feature was discontinued, the Madden Bowl competition continued in a Head-to-Head format.\n\n===Madden Bowl winners===\n* 1995: [[Reggie Brooks]]\n* 1996: [[Reggie Brooks]]\n* 1997: [[Jimmy Spencer (football)|Jimmy Spencer]]\n* 1998: [[Morris Chestnut]]\n* 1999: [[Ray Mickens]]\n* 2000: [[Terry Jackson (running back)|Terry Jackson]]\n* 2001: [[Jacquez Green]]\n* 2002: [[Jacquez Green]]\n* 2003: [[Dwight Freeney]]\n* 2004: [[Dwight Freeney]]\n* 2005: [[Michael Lewis (safety)|Michael Lewis]]\n* 2006: [[Alex Smith (tight end)|Alex Smith]]\n* 2007: [[Alex Smith (tight end)|Alex Smith]]\n* 2008: [[Willis McGahee]]\n* 2009: [[Antonio Bryant]]\n* 2010: [[Maurice Jones-Drew]]\n* 2011: [[Patrick Willis]], [[Chad Ochocinco]], and [[Maria Menounos]]\n* 2012: [[Drew Brees]], [[Jimmy Graham]], and [[Tim Tebow]]\n* 2013: [[LeSean McCoy]]\n* 2014: [[Richard Sherman (American football)|Richard Sherman]]\n* 2015: [[Patrick Peterson]]\n* 2016: [[Eric Berry]]\n\n===Rookie Madden Bowl winners===\n* 2006: [[Alex Smith (tight end)|Alex Smith]]\n* 2007: [[Vince Young]]\n* 2008: [[Devin Thomas]]\n* 2009: [[Vernon Gholston]]\n\nFrom 2016-2017 the NFL Network aired Madden America which was hosted by Dave Grunfeld. Grunfeld would travel across the country meeting and competing against the world's best professional madden players. These players included Eric \"Problem\" Wright, Chris \"Dubby\" McFarland and Michael Skimbo among others.\n\n==Annual EA Super Bowl simulation==\nSince 2004, EA Sports has run a simulation of the Super Bowl using the latest game in the ''Madden NFL'' series and announced the result. The game simulations conducted by EA have correctly predicted 11 of the last 17 Super Bowl winners. The company accurately predicted the final score for the 2015 game and other details, including a score of 24\u201314 in favor of Seattle in the third quarter, despite skepticism within EA that Seattle would lose after a double-digit lead.<ref name=\"exact-score\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/madden-15-predicted-the-exact-score-of-the-super-bowl-1683159462|title=''Madden 15'' Predicted the Exact Score of the Super Bowl|website=Kotaku|first=Jason|last=Schreier|date=February 1, 2015|accessdate=February 1, 2015}}</ref>{{r|helfand20150202}} The predictions were incorrect in 2008, 2011, 2014, 2016, 2018, and 2019. EA also releases a computer-generated description of the simulated game as if it were a summary of the real Super Bowl. The results of the simulated and actual Super Bowl games are listed below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Year\n! rowspan=2| Super<br />Bowl\n! rowspan=2| Madden's winner\n! rowspan=2| Madden's loser\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" width=\"90px\" | Actual<br />score\n! colspan=3 class=\"unsortable\"| Madden's prediction\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"| Madden's<br />record\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"| Sources\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" width=\"90px\" | Score\n! Result\n! Points diff.\n|- style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n|2004\n|align=\"left\"| [[Super Bowl XXXVIII|XXXVIII]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[2003 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[2003 Carolina Panthers season|C