{"title_page": "Breaking Kayfabe", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Breaking Kayfabe\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Cadence Weapon]]\n| cover      = Breaking Kayfabe.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 28, 2005\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 49:40\n| label      = Upper Class Canada\n| producer   = Cadence Weapon and [[Nik Kozub]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Afterparty Babies]]\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\n'''''Breaking Kayfabe''''' is the debut album by Canadian [[rapper]] [[Cadence Weapon]], released in 2005 on Upper Class Recordings. It was also released in the United States by [[Anti-Records]] on March 13, 2007. ''[[kayfabe|Breaking kayfabe]]'' is a [[professional wrestling]] term for \"[[breaking character]]\".\n\n''Breaking Kayfabe'' received positive reviews from critics who praised the 8-bit style beats and intellectual lyrics meshing well together. The album was shortlisted for the [[2006 Polaris Music Prize]]. However, it lost to [[Final Fantasy (band)|Final Fantasy]]'s ''[[He Poos Clouds]]''.\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 80/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/breaking-kayfabe/cadence-weapon|title=Reviews for Breaking Kayfabe by Cadence Weapon|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000480400|pure_url=yes}}|title=Breaking Kayfabe - Cadence Weapon|last=Brown|first=Marisa|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev2Score = 9/10<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/11306/reviews/2409483-|title=Album Review: Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Jones|first=Francis|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=September 19, 2007|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3      = [[Okayplayer]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Okay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.okayplayer.com/reviews/index.php/weblog/more/breaking_kayfabe/|title=Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Mistry|first=Anupa|website=[[Okayplayer]]|accessdate=November 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304105616/http://www.okayplayer.com/reviews/index.php/weblog/more/breaking_kayfabe/|archivedate=March 4, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev4Score = 8.0/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/1801-breaking-kayfabe/|title=Cadence Weapon: Breaking Kayfabe|last=Macia|first=Peter|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=May 3, 2006|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev5Score = B<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/cadence-weapon/breaking-kayfabe.htm|title=Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Mathers|first=Ian|magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=December 19, 2005|accessdate=November 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418051317/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/cadence-weapon/breaking-kayfabe.htm|archivedate=April 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n''Breaking Kayfabe'' garnered highly positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 80, based on 9 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nFrancis Jones of [[Drowned in Sound]] praised the songs for having both production and lyrics feel equal and unique, calling it \"a record that demands and deserves undivided attention, its creator fashioning a brain-searing patchwork of ragged rap, electronic flourishes and truncated rhythms.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/> Marisa Brown of [[AllMusic]] also praised Cadence for crafting electro beats over tracks that carry intelligent lyrics, concluding that \"''Breaking Kayfabe'' is a cohesive set of songs, backpacker in the best of senses, smart and witty and provocative, experimental and well-produced, but at the same time very raw and very real-sounding. It's not often that a debut does all this correctly; listeners would be wise to pay attention.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Peter Macia of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' gave praise to Cadence foregoing hip-hop conventions and instead worked on smart lyricism and video game-inspired production, concluding that it \"may not be his masterpiece, but it hints that he may be capable of one.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Ian Mathers of [[Stylus Magazine]] noted that the production starts to sound droll at first but found it and the lyricism shining bright after a few listens, concluding with, \"Too exciting for the underground (maybe), too weird for the overground (hopefully not), he deserves to be heard by both; I'm willing to bet it's all because he's Canadian.\"<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Tracklist\n| title1 = Oliver Square\n| length1 = 3:33\n| title2 = Sharks\n| length2 = 3:59\n| title3 = Grim Fandango\n| length3 = 3:36\n| title4 = Black Hand\n| length4 = 3:47\n| title5 = 30 Seconds\n| length5 = 3:34\n| title6 = Diamond Cutter\n| length6 = 2:45\n| title7 = Holy Smoke\n| length7 = 3:16\n| title8 = Fathom\n| length8 = 4:01\n| title9 = Turning on Your Sign\n| length9 = 3:44\n| title10 = Lisa's Spider\n| length10 = 2:31\n| title11 = Vicarious\n| length11 = 4:20\n| title12 = Julie Will Jump the Broom\n| length12 = 10:19\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n[[Category:Cadence Weapon albums]]\n[[Category:Upper Class Recordings albums]]\n\n\n{{2005-hiphop-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Breaking Kayfabe\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Cadence Weapon]]\n| cover      = Breaking Kayfabe.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 28, 2005\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 49:40\n| label      = Upper Class Canada\n| producer   = Cadence Weapon and [[Nik Kozub]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Afterparty Babies]]\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\n'''''Breaking Kayfabe''''' is the debut album by Canadian [[rapper]] [[Cadence Weapon]], released in 2005 on Upper Class Recordings. It was also released in the United States by [[Anti-Records]] on March 13, 2007. ''[[kayfabe|Breaking kayfabe]]'' is a [[professional wrestling]] term for \"[[breaking character]]\".\n\n''Breaking Kayfabe'' received positive reviews from critics who praised the 8-bit style beats and intellectual lyrics meshing well together. The album was shortlisted for the [[2006 Polaris Music Prize]]. However, it lost to [[Final Fantasy (band)|Final Fantasy]]'s ''[[He Poos Clouds]]''.\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 80/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/breaking-kayfabe/cadence-weapon|title=Reviews for Breaking Kayfabe by Cadence Weapon|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000480400|pure_url=yes}}|title=Breaking Kayfabe - Cadence Weapon|last=Brown|first=Marisa|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| rev2Score = 9/10<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/11306/reviews/2409483-|title=Album Review: Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Jones|first=Francis|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=September 19, 2007|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3      = [[Okayplayer]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Okay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.okayplayer.com/reviews/index.php/weblog/more/breaking_kayfabe/|title=Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Mistry|first=Anupa|website=[[Okayplayer]]|accessdate=November 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304105616/http://www.okayplayer.com/reviews/index.php/weblog/more/breaking_kayfabe/|archivedate=March 4, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev4Score = 8.0/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/1801-breaking-kayfabe/|title=Cadence Weapon: Breaking Kayfabe|last=Macia|first=Peter|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=May 3, 2006|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''\n| rev5Score = B<ref name=\"Stylus\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/cadence-weapon/breaking-kayfabe.htm|title=Cadence Weapon - Breaking Kayfabe|last=Mathers|first=Ian|magazine=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=December 19, 2005|accessdate=November 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418051317/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/cadence-weapon/breaking-kayfabe.htm|archivedate=April 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n''Breaking Kayfabe'' garnered highly positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 80, based on 9 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nFrancis Jones of [[Drowned in Sound]] praised the songs for having both production and lyrics feel equal and unique, calling it \"a record that demands and deserves undivided attention, its creator fashioning a brain-searing patchwork of ragged rap, electronic flourishes and truncated rhythms.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/> Marisa Brown of [[AllMusic]] also praised Cadence for crafting electro beats over tracks that carry intelligent lyrics, concluding that \"''Breaking Kayfabe'' is a cohesive set of songs, backpacker in the best of senses, smart and witty and provocative, experimental and well-produced, but at the same time very raw and very real-sounding. It's not often that a debut does all this correctly; listeners would be wise to pay attention.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Peter Macia of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' gave praise to Cadence foregoing hip-hop conventions and instead worked on smart lyricism and video game-inspired production, concluding that it \"may not be his masterpiece, but it hints that he may be capable of one.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Ian Mathers of [[Stylus Magazine]] noted that the production starts to sound droll at first but found it and the lyricism shining bright after a few listens, concluding with, \"Too exciting for the underground (maybe), too weird for the overground (hopefully not), he deserves to be heard by both; I'm willing to bet it's all because he's Canadian.\"<ref name=\"Stylus\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Tracklist\n| title1 = Oliver Square\n| length1 = 3:33\n| title2 = Sharks\n| length2 = 3:59\n| title3 = Grim Fandango\n| length3 = 3:36\n| title4 = Black Hand\n| length4 = 3:47\n| title5 = 30 Seconds\n| length5 = 3:34\n| title6 = Diamond Cutter\n| length6 = 2:45\n| title7 = Holy Smoke\n| length7 = 3:16\n| title8 = Fathom\n| length8 = 4:01\n| title9 = Turning on Your Sign\n| length9 = 3:44\n| title10 = Lisa's Spider\n| length10 = 2:31\n| title11 = Vicarious\n| length11 = 4:20\n| title12 = Julie Will Jump the Broom\n| length12 = 10:19\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n[[Category:Cadence Weapon albums]]\n[[Category:Upper Class Recordings albums]]\n\n\n{{2005-hiphop-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DepressedPer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:C/E.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breaking_Kayfabe"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk", "text_new": "{{other people||Thomas Howard (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox noble\n| name                 = Thomas Howard\n| title                = [[Duke of Norfolk]]\n| image                =ThomasHoward4HerzogvonNorfolk.jpg\n| caption               =\n| spouse               = [[Mary FitzAlan]] <br> [[Margaret Audley, Duchess of Norfolk|Margaret Audley]] <br>  [[Elizabeth Leyburne]]\n| issue             = [[Philip Howard, 20th Earl of Arundel]] <br> [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk]] <br> [[Lord William Howard]] <br> Lady Elizabeth Howard <br> [[Lady Margaret Sackville (1562\u20131591)|Lady Margaret Howard]] <br> \n| full name            =\n| noble family          =[[House of Howard|Howard]]| father               =[[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]\n\n| mother               =[[Frances de Vere, Countess of Surrey|Frances de Vere]]\n| birth_date        =10 March 1536\n| death_date        ={{death date and age|1572|6|2|1536|3|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tower Hill]] ,  [[London]],  England\n}}\n[[File:Arms of the Duke of Norfolk.svg|thumb|170px|Arms of Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk.]]\n'''Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG}} (10 March 1536{{snd}}2 June 1572) was an English nobleman and politician. Although hailing from a family with strong Catholic leanings, he was raised a Protestant. He was a second cousin  of Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] through her maternal grandmother, and held many high offices during her reign.\n\nNorfolk was the son of the poet [[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]. He commissioned [[Thomas Tallis]], probably in 1567, to compose his renowned [[motet]] in forty voice-parts, ''[[Spem in alium]]''.\n\n==Early life, family, and religion==\nNorfolk was taught as a child by [[John Foxe]], the Protestant [[martyrology|martyrologist]],<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Norfolk, Earls and Dukes of|volume=19|page=744}}</ref> who remained a lifelong recipient of Norfolk's patronage.  His father predeceased his grandfather, so Norfolk inherited the [[Duke of Norfolk|Dukedom of Norfolk]] upon the death of his grandfather, [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]] in 1554.\n\nHe was a second cousin of Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] through her maternal grandmother, [[Elizabeth Boleyn, Countess of Wiltshire|Lady Elizabeth Howard]], and he was trusted with public office despite his family's history and leanings towards [[Catholicism]] (although he was brought up a Protestant).\n\n==Career==\nWhile still young, Norfolk was Earl Marshal of England and Queen's Lieutenant in the North. From February to July 1560, Norfolk was commander of the English army in Scotland in support of the [[Lords of the Congregation]] opposing [[Mary of Guise]]. He negotiated the February 1560 [[Treaty of Berwick (1560)|Treaty of Berwick]] by which the Congregation invited English assistance,<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 1 (1898), 323, 440.</ref> and after the [[Treaty of Edinburgh]] was signed in July of that year he was able to return to the court.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nNorfolk was the Principal of the commission at York in 1568 to hear evidence against [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] presented by [[Regent Moray]], including the [[casket letters]].<ref>HMC: ''Manuscripts of the Earl of Salisbury at Hatfield'', vol.1 (1883), p. 461.</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles and execution==\nHaving married and lost three wives by 1567, and despite having presided at the York commission, Norfolk schemed to marry [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. [[William Maitland of Lethington]] favoured the proposed union, and Mary herself consented to it, but Norfolk was unwilling to take up arms. He was briefly involved in the [[Northern Rebellion]] in an attempt to free and marry Mary, and Elizabeth ordered his arrest for this in October 1569.  He was imprisoned for nine months.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\nFollowing his release in August 1570, and after some hesitation, he participated in the [[Ridolfi plot]] with King [[Philip II of Spain]] to put Mary on the English throne and restore [[Catholicism]] in England. The plot was revealed to the queen's minister [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|Lord Burghley]],<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> and after a trial in January 1572, in which he was found unanimously guilty, Norfolk was executed for treason in Tower Hill, London, in June.<ref>[[David Jardine (barrister)|Jardine, David]].  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ScBCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA121 Criminal Trials, Supplying Copious Illustrations of the Important Periods of English History During the Reigns of Queen Elizabeth and James I.: To which is Added a Narrative of the Gunpowder Plot, with Historical Prefaces and Notes]'', Volume 1, pp. 121-245 (Nattali and Bond, 1847).</ref><ref>[[Matthew Bacon|Bacon, Matthew]] et al.  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=m2kyAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA399 A New Abridgment of the Law with Large Additions and Corrections]'', Volume 9, p. 399 (T. Davis, 1846).</ref> He is buried at the [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula]] within the walls of the [[Tower of London]].\n\nNorfolk's lands and titles were forfeit, although much of the estate was later restored to his sons. The title of [[Duke of Norfolk]] was restored, four generations later, to his great-great-grandson [[Thomas Howard, 5th Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]].\n\n==Marriages and issue==\n===First wife===\n[[File:Hans Eworth called Mary Fitzalan Duchess of Norfolk.jpg|thumb|170px|Mary FitzAlan]]\n[[File:MargaretAudley.jpg|thumb|170px|Margaret Audley]]\n[[File:Elizabeth leyburne.jpg|thumb|170px|Portrait of Elizabeth Leyburne attributed to [[Hans Eworth]], c. 1560]]\nThomas Howard's first wife was [[Mary FitzAlan]], who after the death of her brother Henry in 1556 became heiress to the [[Arundel]] estates of her father [[Henry FitzAlan, 19th Earl of Arundel]].  She died after a year of marriage, having given birth to a son:\n\n* [[Philip Howard, 20th Earl of Arundel|Philip Howard]] (28 June 1557{{snd}}19 October 1595), who  became the 20th Earl of Arundel.\n\nIt is from this marriage that modern Dukes of Norfolk derive their surname of 'FitzAlan-Howard' and their seat in Arundel. Though her funeral effigy is found at [[St Michael the Archangel, Framlingham|Framlingham church]], Mary FitzAlan was not buried there but first at the church of [[St. Clement Danes]], [[Temple Bar, London|Temple Bar]] and then, under the direction of her grandson's will, at Arundel.\n\n===Second wife===\nNorfolk next married another heiress, [[Margaret Audley, Duchess of Norfolk|Margaret Audley]],<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp88204/margaret-howard-ne-dudley-duchess-of-norfolk \"Margaret Howard\", National Portrait Gallery]</ref> widow of Sir [[Henry Dudley (1531\u20131557)|Henry Dudley]] and daughter of [[Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden]]. Margaret's children by her marriage to Norfolk were:\n* [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk]];\n* [[Lord William Howard]], ancestor of the [[Earls of Carlisle]];\n* Lady Elizabeth Howard (died in childhood);\n* [[Lady Margaret Sackville (1562\u20131591)|Lady Margaret Howard]]<ref>http://www.geni.com/people/Margaret-Howard/6000000000151561135</ref>\n\nMargaret Audley Howard's tomb effigy is found at [[St Michael the Archangel, Framlingham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/peter.fairweather/docs/framlingham.htm |title=Churchmouse: Framlingham, Suffolk. Church of St. Michael the Archangel |publisher=Homepage.ntlworld.com |date=2 May 2000 |accessdate=7 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309144503/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/peter.fairweather/docs/framlingham.htm |archivedate=9 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Third wife===\nAfter Margaret's death in 1563, Norfolk married [[Elizabeth Leyburne]] (1536{{snd}}4 September 1567), widow of [[Thomas Dacre, 4th Baron Dacre]] of [[Gillesland]] and daughter of Sir [[James Leyburn]].\n\nNorfolk's three sons by his first two wives, Philip, Thomas, and William, married, respectively, [[Anne Howard, Countess of Arundel|Anne]], Margaret, and Elizabeth Dacre. The Dacre sisters were the daughters of Elizabeth Leyburne by her marriage to Thomas Dacre and were, thereby, stepsisters to Norfolk's sons.\n\n===Attempted fourth marriage===\nAfter Norfolk's third wife's death in 1567, [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] fled to England in 1568 and was imprisoned by [[Elizabeth I|Queen Elizabeth]]. Thomas Howard was suggested as a husband for her as he was a cousin to Queen Elizabeth and the wealthiest landowner in the country. Together they would have a strong claim on England's throne as Mary was also Elizabeth's cousin. This suited Norfolk as he was ambitious and felt Elizabeth consistently undervalued him. Therefore, Norfolk supported the [[Northern Rebellion]] in 1569 in an effort to free and marry [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. It is still debated whether this plot actually planned to overthrow Elizabeth or even if Mary knew about it. Howard soon lost his nerve and the plan failed, but he made another effort to marry Mary in 1571 as part of the [[Ridolfi Plot]]. This plot planned to murder Elizabeth and free Mary. She would then marry Howard so that they could take the throne. Elizabeth's government discovered the plot and Howard's servants betrayed him under torture. Norfolk was imprisoned by [[Elizabeth I|Queen Elizabeth]] and put on trial in January 1572. He was found guilty unanimously and beheaded on Tower Hill, London, in June.<ref>Hodder Education History for Edexcel: Early Elizabethan England</ref>\n\n==Depictions==\n*Thomas Howard appears as a character in the [[Philippa Gregory]] novels ''The Virgin's Lover'' and ''The Other Queen'', and in the novel ''I, Elizabeth'' by [[Rosalind Miles]].\n*A highly fictionalized version of the 4th Duke of Norfolk appears as a villain, played by [[Christopher Eccleston]], in the 1998 film ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]''. \n*Another version of the Duke is in the BBC mini-series ''[[The Virgin Queen (TV serial)|The Virgin Queen]]'', played by [[Kevin McKidd]].\n*In the [[Channel 4]] [[documentary]] ''Elizabeth'' (2000) presented by [[David Starkey]], the Duke is portrayed by actor John Gully.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|title=Ancestors of Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk \n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk'''\n|2= 2. [[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]\n|3= 3. [[Frances de Vere, Countess of Surrey]]\n|4= 4. [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]]\n|5= 5. [[Elizabeth Howard, Duchess of Norfolk|Elizabeth Stafford, Duchess of Norfolk]]\n|6= 6. [[John de Vere, 15th Earl of Oxford]]\n|7= 7. [[Elizabeth Trussell, Countess of Oxford]]\n|8= 8. [[Thomas Howard, 2nd Duke of Norfolk]]\n|9= 9. [[Elizabeth Tilney]]\n|10= 10. [[Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham]]\n|11= 11. [[Eleanor Percy, Duchess of Buckingham]]\n|12= 12. John de Vere\n|13= 13. Alice Kilrington\n|14= 14. Sir Edward Trussell of Kibbleston\n|15= 15. Margaret Dunn\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dukes of Norfolk family tree]]\n*[[John George Howard]], a Toronto architect who claims to be related to the Duke.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book | title=The marvellous chance: Thomas Howard, Fourth Duke of Norfolk, and the Ridolphi plot, 1570-1572 | first=Francis | last=Edwards | date=1968 | isbn=0-246-64474-5 | ref=harv | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/marvellouschance0000edwa }}\n*{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7o_AAAAYAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=Murdin, William : Collection of State Papers, 1571-1596 | place= London | date=1759 |ref=harv}}  papers from Norfolk's treason trial 1568\u20131572.\n*{{cite book | title=Thomas Howard, Fourth duke of Norfolk | first= Neville |last= Williams | date=1965 | asin= B0007DRE5Y }}\n*{{cite book | title= Thomas Howard: Fourth Duke of Norfolk | place= The Benedictine Brethren of Glendalough | editor= William Cooke Taylor | date=2005 |isbn= 1-4254-6159-X | ref=harv }}\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Howard, Thomas (1536-1572)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Earl Marshal]]\n | before = [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|The Duke of Norfolk]]\n | after  = [[George Talbot, 6th Earl of Shrewsbury|The Earl of Shrewsbury]]\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Thomas Radclyffe, 3rd Earl of Sussex|The Earl of Sussex]]\n | title  = [[Lord Lieutenant of Norfolk]]\n | years  = 1559&ndash;1572\n | after  = Unknown}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | rows   = 3\n | before = [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Duke of Norfolk]]|creation=3rd creation\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572 }}\n{{s-vac\n | next= [[Thomas Howard, 5th Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]] }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Earl of Surrey]]|creation=3rd creation\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572 }}\n{{s-vac\n | next= [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel|Thomas Howard]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Baron Mowbray]]\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572 }}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Philip Howard, 1st Earl of Arundel|Philip Howard]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Dukes of Norfolk}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norfolk, Thomas Howard, 4th Duke Of}}\n[[Category:1536 births]]\n[[Category:1572 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Norfolk|304]]\n[[Category:Earls of Surrey|303]]\n[[Category:Earls Marshal]]\n[[Category:Barons Mowbray]]\n[[Category:Barons Segrave|*16]]\n[[Category:Howard family (English aristocracy)|Thomas Howard, 04th Duke of Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Norfolk]]\n[[Category:People executed under the Tudors for treason against England]]\n[[Category:People of the Elizabethan era|Howard, Thomas]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:People convicted under a bill of attainder]]\n[[Category:Executions at the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Prisoners in the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Executed English people]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Saint Michael]]\n[[Category:People executed by Tudor England by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed under Elizabeth I of England]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter ad Vincula (London)]]\n[[Category:English politicians convicted of crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Thomas Howard (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox noble\n| name                 = Thomas Howard\n| title                = [[Duke of Norfolk]]\n| image                =ThomasHoward4HerzogvonNorfolk.jpg\n| caption               =\n| spouse               = [[Mary FitzAlan]] <br> [[Margaret Audley, Duchess of Norfolk|Margaret Audley]] <br>  [[Elizabeth Leyburne]]\n| issue             = [[Philip Howard, 20th Earl of Arundel]] <br> [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk]] <br> [[Lord William Howard]] <br> Lady Elizabeth Howard <br> [[Lady Margaret Sackville (1562\u20131591)|Lady Margaret Howard]] <br> \n| full name            =\n| noble family          =[[House of Howard|Howard]]| father               =[[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]\n\n| mother               =[[Frances de Vere, Countess of Surrey|Frances de Vere]]\n| birth_date        =10 March 1536\n| death_date        ={{death date and age|1572|6|2|1536|3|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Tower Hill]] ,  [[London]],  England\n}}\n[[File:Arms of the Duke of Norfolk.svg|thumb|170px|Arms of Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk.]]\n'''Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG}} (10 March 1536{{snd}}2 June 1572) was an English nobleman and politician. Although hailing from a family with strong Catholic leanings, he was raised a Protestant. He was a second cousin  of Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] through her maternal grandmother, and held many high offices during her reign.\n\nNorfolk was the son of the poet [[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]. He commissioned [[Thomas Tallis]], probably in 1567, to compose his renowned [[motet]] in forty voice-parts, ''[[Spem in alium]]''.\n\n==Early life, family, and religion==\nNorfolk was taught as a child by [[John Foxe]], the Protestant [[martyrology|martyrologist]],<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Norfolk, Earls and Dukes of|volume=19|page=744}}</ref> who remained a lifelong recipient of Norfolk's patronage.  His father predeceased his grandfather, so Norfolk inherited the [[Duke of Norfolk|Dukedom of Norfolk]] upon the death of his grandfather, [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]] in 1554.\n\nHe was a second cousin of Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] through her maternal grandmother, [[Elizabeth Boleyn, Countess of Wiltshire|Lady Elizabeth Howard]], and he was trusted with public office despite his family's history and leanings towards [[Catholicism]] (although he was brought up a Protestant).\n\n==Career==\nWhile still young, Norfolk was Earl Marshal of England and Queen's Lieutenant in the North. From February to July 1560, Norfolk was commander of the English army in Scotland in support of the [[Lords of the Congregation]] opposing [[Mary of Guise]]. He negotiated the February 1560 [[Treaty of Berwick (1560)|Treaty of Berwick]] by which the Congregation invited English assistance,<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 1 (1898), 323, 440.</ref> and after the [[Treaty of Edinburgh]] was signed in July of that year he was able to return to the court.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\n\nNorfolk was the Principal of the commission at York in 1568 to hear evidence against [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] presented by [[Regent Moray]], including the [[casket letters]].<ref>HMC: ''Manuscripts of the Earl of Salisbury at Hatfield'', vol.1 (1883), p. 461.</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles and execution==\nHaving married and lost three wives by 1567, and despite having presided at the York commission, Norfolk schemed to marry [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. [[William Maitland of Lethington]] favoured the proposed union, and Mary herself consented to it, but Norfolk was unwilling to take up arms. He was briefly involved in the [[Northern Rebellion]] in an attempt to free and marry Mary, and Elizabeth ordered his arrest for this in October 1569.  He was imprisoned for nine months.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/>\nFollowing his release in August 1570, and after some hesitation, he participated in the [[Ridolfi plot]] with King [[Philip II of Spain]] to put Mary on the English throne and restore [[Catholicism]] in England. The plot was revealed to the queen's minister [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|Lord Burghley]],<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> and after a trial in January 1572, in which he was found unanimously guilty, Norfolk was executed for treason in Tower Hill, London, in June.<ref>[[David Jardine (barrister)|Jardine, David]].  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ScBCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA121 Criminal Trials, Supplying Copious Illustrations of the Important Periods of English History During the Reigns of Queen Elizabeth and James I.: To which is Added a Narrative of the Gunpowder Plot, with Historical Prefaces and Notes]'', Volume 1, pp. 121-245 (Nattali and Bond, 1847).</ref><ref>[[Matthew Bacon|Bacon, Matthew]] et al.  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=m2kyAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA399 A New Abridgment of the Law with Large Additions and Corrections]'', Volume 9, p. 399 (T. Davis, 1846).</ref> He is buried at the [[Church of St Peter ad Vincula]] within the walls of the [[Tower of London]].\n\nNorfolk's lands and titles were forfeit, although much of the estate was later restored to his sons. The title of [[Duke of Norfolk]] was restored, four generations later, to his great-great-grandson [[Thomas Howard, 5th Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]].\n\n==Marriages and issue==\n===First wife===\n[[File:Hans Eworth called Mary Fitzalan Duchess of Norfolk.jpg|thumb|170px|Mary FitzAlan]]\n[[File:MargaretAudley.jpg|thumb|170px|Margaret Audley]]\n[[File:Elizabeth leyburne.jpg|thumb|170px|Portrait of Elizabeth Leyburne attributed to [[Hans Eworth]], c. 1560]]\nThomas Howard's first wife was [[Mary FitzAlan]], who after the death of her brother Henry in 1556 became heiress to the [[Arundel]] estates of her father [[Henry FitzAlan, 19th Earl of Arundel]].  She died after a year of marriage, having given birth to a son:\n\n* [[Philip Howard, 20th Earl of Arundel|Philip Howard]] (28 June 1557{{snd}}19 October 1595), who  became the 20th Earl of Arundel.\n\nIt is from this marriage that modern Dukes of Norfolk derive their surname of 'FitzAlan-Howard' and their seat in Arundel. Though her funeral effigy is found at [[St Michael the Archangel, Framlingham|Framlingham church]], Mary FitzAlan was not buried there but first at the church of [[St. Clement Danes]], [[Temple Bar, London|Temple Bar]] and then, under the direction of her grandson's will, at Arundel.\n\n===Second wife===\nNorfolk next married another heiress, [[Margaret Audley, Duchess of Norfolk|Margaret Audley]],<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp88204/margaret-howard-ne-dudley-duchess-of-norfolk \"Margaret Howard\", National Portrait Gallery]</ref> widow of Sir [[Henry Dudley (1531\u20131557)|Henry Dudley]] and daughter of [[Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden]]. Margaret's children by her marriage to Norfolk were:\n* [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk]];\n* [[Lord William Howard]], ancestor of the [[Earls of Carlisle]];\n* Lady Elizabeth Howard (died in childhood);\n* [[Lady Margaret Sackville (1562\u20131591)|Lady Margaret Howard]]<ref>http://www.geni.com/people/Margaret-Howard/6000000000151561135</ref>\n\nMargaret Audley Howard's tomb effigy is found at [[St Michael the Archangel, Framlingham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/peter.fairweather/docs/framlingham.htm |title=Churchmouse: Framlingham, Suffolk. Church of St. Michael the Archangel |publisher=Homepage.ntlworld.com |date=2 May 2000 |accessdate=7 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309144503/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/peter.fairweather/docs/framlingham.htm |archivedate=9 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Third wife===\nAfter Margaret's death in 1563, Norfolk married [[Elizabeth Leyburne]] (1536{{snd}}4 September 1567), widow of [[Thomas Dacre, 4th Baron Dacre]] of [[Gillesland]] and daughter of Sir [[James Leyburn]].\n\nNorfolk's three sons by his first two wives, Philip, Thomas, and William, married, respectively, [[Anne Howard, Countess of Arundel|Anne]], Margaret, and Elizabeth Dacre. The Dacre sisters were the daughters of Elizabeth Leyburne by her marriage to Thomas Dacre and were, thereby, stepsisters to Norfolk's sons.\n\n===Attempted fourth marriage===\nAfter Norfolk's third wife's death in 1567, [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] fled to England in 1568 and was imprisoned by [[Elizabeth I|Queen Elizabeth]]. Thomas Howard was suggested as a husband for her as he was a cousin to Queen Elizabeth and the wealthiest landowner in the country. Together they would have a strong claim on England's throne as Mary was also Elizabeth's cousin. This suited Norfolk as he was ambitious and felt Elizabeth consistently undervalued him. Therefore, Norfolk supported the [[Northern Rebellion]] in 1569 in an effort to free and marry [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. It is still debated whether this plot actually planned to overthrow Elizabeth or even if Mary knew about it. Howard soon lost his nerve and the plan failed, but he made another effort to marry Mary in 1571 as part of the [[Ridolfi Plot]]. This plot planned to murder Elizabeth and free Mary. She would then marry Howard so that they could take the throne. Elizabeth's government discovered the plot and Howard's servants betrayed him under torture. Norfolk was imprisoned by [[Elizabeth I|Queen Elizabeth]] and put on trial in January 1572. He was found guilty unanimously and beheaded on Tower Hill, London, in June.<ref>Hodder Education History for Edexcel: Early Elizabethan England</ref>\n\n==Depictions==\n*Thomas Howard appears as a character in the [[Philippa Gregory]] novels ''The Virgin's Lover'' and ''The Other Queen'', and in the novel ''I, Elizabeth'' by [[Rosalind Miles]].\n*A highly fictionalized version of the 4th Duke of Norfolk appears as a villain, played by [[Christopher Eccleston]], in the 1998 film ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]''. \n*Another version of the Duke is in the BBC mini-series ''[[The Virgin Queen (TV serial)|The Virgin Queen]]'', played by [[Kevin McKidd]].\n*In the [[Channel 4]] [[documentary]] ''Elizabeth'' (2000) presented by [[David Starkey]], the Duke is portrayed by actor John Gully.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|title=Ancestors of Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk \n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk'''\n|2= 2. [[Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey]]\n|3= 3. [[Frances de Vere, Countess of Surrey]]\n|4= 4. [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk]]\n|5= 5. [[Elizabeth Howard, Duchess of Norfolk|Elizabeth Stafford, Duchess of Norfolk]]\n|6= 6. [[John de Vere, 15th Earl of Oxford]]\n|7= 7. [[Elizabeth Trussell, Countess of Oxford]]\n|8= 8. [[Thomas Howard, 2nd Duke of Norfolk]]\n|9= 9. [[Elizabeth Tilney]]\n|10= 10. [[Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham]]\n|11= 11. [[Eleanor Percy, Duchess of Buckingham]]\n|12= 12. John de Vere\n|13= 13. Alice Kilrington\n|14= 14. Sir Edward Trussell of Kibbleston\n|15= 15. Margaret Dunn\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dukes of Norfolk family tree]]\n*[[John George Howard]], a Toronto architect who claims to be related to the Duke.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book | title=The marvellous chance: Thomas Howard, Fourth Duke of Norfolk, and the Ridolphi plot, 1570-1572 | first=Francis | last=Edwards | date=1968 | isbn=0-246-64474-5 | ref=harv | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/marvellouschance0000edwa }}\n*{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7o_AAAAYAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=Murdin, William : Collection of State Papers, 1571-1596 | place= London | date=1759 |ref=harv}}  papers from Norfolk's treason trial 1568-1572.\n*{{cite book | title=Thomas Howard, Fourth duke of Norfolk | first= Neville |last= Williams | date=1965 | asin= B0007DRE5Y }}\n*{{cite book | title= Thomas Howard: Fourth Duke of Norfolk | place= The Benedictine Brethren of Glendalough | editor= William Cooke Taylor | date=2005 |isbn= 1-4254-6159-X | ref=harv }}\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Howard, Thomas (1536-1572)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Earl Marshal]]\n | before = [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|The Duke of Norfolk]]\n | after  = [[George Talbot, 6th Earl of Shrewsbury|The Earl of Shrewsbury]]\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Thomas Radclyffe, 3rd Earl of Sussex|The Earl of Sussex]]\n | title  = [[Lord Lieutenant of Norfolk]]\n | years  = 1559&ndash;1572\n | after  = Unknown}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | rows   = 3\n | before = [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Duke of Norfolk]]|creation=3rd creation\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572 }}\n{{s-vac\n | next= [[Thomas Howard, 5th Duke of Norfolk|Thomas Howard]] }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Earl of Surrey]]|creation=3rd creation\n | years  = 1554&ndash;1572 }}\n{{s-vac\n | next= 